# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: air-national-guard
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] The **100th Fighter Squadron** is a unit of the Alabama Air National Guard 187th Fighter Wing located at Dannelly Field, Alabama.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] The 100th is equipped with the Lockheed Martin F-35A Lightning II.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] The squadron was one of the Tuskegee Airmen squadrons during World War II, one of the famous all-black squadrons of the 332d Fighter Group, activated on 19 February 1942 at Tuskegee Army Air Field, Alabama.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] It was returned to duty in 2007 as a replacement of the 160th Fighter Squadron so the state could honor the legacy of the Tuskegee Airmen.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] Established in February 1942 at Tuskegee Army Air Field, Alabama to train African-American flight cadets graduated from the Tuskegee Institute Army contract flying school.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] At Tuskegee, the squadron performed advanced combat flying training.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] As the number of graduated from the Tuskegee school grew, two additional squadrons the 301st and 302nd Fighter Squadrons were activated at Tuskegee Army Air Field, forming the 332nd Fighter Group.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] Due to the segregated status of the Army Air Forces in 1942 and the reluctance by the service to deploy African Americans into combat, the 332nd remained in an extended training status.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] The Group was transferred to Selfridge Field, near Detroit, Michigan in March 1943 after the decision was reached to deploy the unit.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] Racial tensions in the Detroit area, however, forced a move to Oscoda Army Air Field, in isolated northeast Michigan the next month where the final training of the unit was performed by First Air Force.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] However, the unit was delayed again going into combat, and also was sent back to Selfridge upon completion of training at Oscoda to perform Air defense flights over the Detroit area beginning in July 1943.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] For six months, the unit remained at Selfridge until pressure on the Army led to the decision to deploy the 100th to the Fifteenth Air Force in Italy at the end of 1943, under the command of Robert B.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] Tresville, to support the strategic aerial bombardment campaign being carried out by Boeing B-17 Flying Fortress and Consolidated B-24 Liberator Heavy bombers from newly established air bases in the Foggia, Italy area.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] As the Italian Campaign pushed further north into Italy during 1944, the squadron moved to operate from forward captured air bases, flying bomber escort missions initially with Republic P-47 Thunderbolts, then being upgraded to the long-range North American P-51D Mustang fighter.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] In combat, the unit engaged enemy forces in the Rome-Arno area, then during the D-Day landings in France, took part in the Normandy and Northern France campaigns.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] It returned to the MTO in August 1944, flying combat missions supporting Operation Dragoon, the invasion of southern France, and attacking enemy targets in Northern Italy, Po Valley, the German Rhineland and the Western Allied invasion of Germany during March and April 1945.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] With the end of the War in Europe in May 1945, the squadron was returned to Southern Italy, being stationed at Lucera Airfield, near Foggia where the unit slowly was demobilized and personnel returned to the United States.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] The 100th Fighter Squadron was inactivated at Camp Kilmer, New Jersey in mid-October 1945.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] The 332nd was reactivated as part of Tactical Air Command Ninth Air Force at Lockbourne Army Air Base (Later Lockbourne Air Force Base), near Columbus, Ohio in July 1947, again as a segregated African-American unit of the Army Air Forces (later United States Air Force).
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] At Lockbourne, the Wing was equipped with new F-47N Thunderbolts that were designed for very-long range flights in the Pacific Theater to attack ground targets in the Japanese Home Islands.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] However, the aircraft were never deployed due to the sudden end of the War in August 1945.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] At Lockbourne, the squadron participated in firepower demonstrations, gunnery training, and operational missions to maintain combat proficiency.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] The African-American segregated unit was inactivated in July 1949 as a result of President Harry S.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] EO 9981 abolished racial discrimination in the United States Armed Forces.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] The 100th's personnel and equipment were reassigned to other units.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] The **100th Air Refueling Squadron** was activated by Strategic Air Command (SAC) in 1953, and equipped with Boeing KB-29 Superfortress tankers, based at Robins Air Force Base, near Warner Robins, Georgia.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] The squadron primarily performed air refueling of SAC's Boeing B-50 Superfortress medium bombers using a primitive "looped hose" refueling system.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] The 100th Air Refueling Squadron continued to operate from Pease until the end of the B-47 and Reflex era in 1966, at which point the unit was inactivated.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] In 1985, the 100th Fighter Squadron and 100th Air Refueling Squadron were consolidated into a single unit.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] Air Training Command reactivated the consolidated unit 100th as the **100th Flying Training Squadron** at Williams Air Force Base, Phoenix, Arizona in September 1989 to demonstrate the feasibility of Air Training Command's plan for five flying training squadrons at each pilot training base.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] Its instructor pilots provided incoming pilots qualification in Cessna T-37 Tweet and northrop T-38 Talon aircraft, and as instructor pilots.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] The squadron was inactivated as part of the post-Cold War drawdown of the Air Force in 1993.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] The 100th was again reactivated as a flying training squadron at Randolph Air Force Base, Texas, equipped with Beechcraft T-6 Texan II, Raytheon T-1 Jayhawk and Northrop T-38C Talon trainers.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] It provided flight training to new air force pilot trainees throughout the early 21st century.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] In 2007, the Alabama legislature requested the National Guard Bureau to allow the Alabama Air National Guard to replace its 160th Fighter Squadron with the **100th Fighter Squadron** so the state could honor the legacy of the World War II Tuskegee Airmen.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] This was obtained from the Air Force and on 12 September 2009, the 100th Flying Training Squadron was inactivated.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] The designation was transferred to the National Guard Bureau by the Air Force and it was allotted to the Alabama ANG.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] As a result, the 160th Fighter Squadron was inactivated, and the new 100th Fighter Squadron assumed its personnel, equipment and aircraft.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] The 160th Fighter Squadron stood down in a ceremony at Montgomery Air National Guard Base, on 13 September 2007, with the 100th Fighter Squadron standing up.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] From the onset the squadron started training on the block 30 version of the General Dynamics F-16C/D Fighting Falcon that carried over from the 160th.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] The squadron flies the F-16 in a traditional air defense and conventional attack role.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] In August 2009, the 100th Expeditionary Fighter Squadron deployed 240 airmen and aircraft to Balad Air Base, Iraq as part of the 332nd Expeditionary Fighter Squadron supporting Operation Iraq Freedom.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] This was the first deployment of the 100th FS to the middle east and over 2,000 hours were flown and Precision Guided Munitions were employed.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] The unit returned to Montgomery in November 2009.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] The squadron deployed to Romania in August 2012 to participate in Dacian Viper 2012, a three-week joint exercise with the Romanian Air Force.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] The squadron returned to Romania in 2015, taking part in combined air operations during the Dacian Viper 2015 exercise.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] In December 2017, the Air Force announced that the 100th was one of two Air National Guard squadrons selected for equipping with the Lockheed Martin F-35 Lightning II.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] The conversion to the fifth-generation jet fighter is scheduled for 2023.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] On 21 April, the squadron retired its F-16 fighters and will continue its conversion process to the F-35 which arrived in December.
[src:air-national-guard/100th-fighter-squadron] Full operational readiness is to be achieved until February 2026.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-air-refueling-wing] The **101st Air Refueling Wing (101 ARW)** is a unit of the Maine Air National Guard, stationed at Bangor Air National Guard Base, Bangor, Maine.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-air-refueling-wing] If activated to federal service with the United States Air Force, the 101 ARW is operationally-gained by the Air Mobility Command (AMC).
[src:air-national-guard/101st-air-refueling-wing] The mission of the 101st FIW was the air defense of New England.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The **157th Air Refueling Wing** is a unit of the New Hampshire Air National Guard, stationed at Pease Air National Guard Base, New Hampshire, United States.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] If activated to federal service, the Wing is gained by the United States Air Force Air Mobility Command.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The direct predecessor to the 101st Air Refueling Wing is the World War II 311th Fighter Group.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The 311th was one of only three groups to use the A-36 Apache dive bomber version of the North American P-51 Mustang.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] It was created in 1942 as a light bombardment group, training with the Vultee Vengeance, before moving on to the A-36 (and the P-51) when it entered combat in India as part of the Tenth Air Force.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Trained with Vultee V-72 Vengeance aircraft.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Moved to India, via Australia, July–September 1943.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Operating from India and using A-36A Apaches.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The unit's aircraft had yellow tails with two black bands, the 530th Fighter Squadron having its diagonal bands sloping from top right to bottom left, while the other two squadrons had theirs either vertical or sloping the opposite way.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The red nose was also a squadron marking.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Many planes of this group had a girl's name on the nose, but very few had any artwork.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Converted to North American P-51C Mustangs in May 1944.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Moved to Burma in July and continued to support ground forces, including Merrill's Marauders; also flew numerous sweeps over enemy airfields in central and southern Burma.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Moved to China in August 1944 and assigned to Fourteenth Air Force.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Escorted bombers, flew interception missions, struck the enemy's communications, and supported ground operations, serving in combat until the end of the war.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Ferried P-51's from India for the Chinese Air Force in November 1945.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The 134th FIS becoming the group's flying squadron.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Other squadrons assigned into the group were the 101st Material Squadron, 101st Air Base Squadron, and the 101st USAF Dispensary.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The 101st Fighter Group (AD) was assigned to the Maine Air National Guard 101st Air Defense Wing.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The wartime 311th Fighter Group was re-designated as the '*101st Fighter Group*, and was allotted to the Maine Air National Guard, on 24 May 1946.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] It was organized at Camp Keyes, Augusta, Maine, and was extended federal recognition on 4 April 1947 by the National Guard Bureau.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The 101st Fighter Group was bestowed the lineage, history, honors, and colors of the 311th Fighter Group, and all predecessor units.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The group was assigned to the Massachusetts ANG 67th Fighter Wing, operationally gained by Continental Air Command.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The three squadrons were all re-designations of the 311th Fighter Group's operational squadrons during World War II.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] All were initially equipped with F-47D Thunderbolts, with a mission of air defense of their respective states.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] In the summer of 1948, the 132d Fighter Squadron replaced their F-47 Thunderbolts with jet F-80C Shooting Stars and were re-designated with the "Jet Propelled" suffix on 1 August.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The 134th received Very Long-Range F-51H Mustangs in the summer of 1950.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The unit assumed the F-94 Starfire aircraft of the 134th FIS and the air defense mission of New Hampshire.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] By April 1958, the 101st counted nearly 700 officers and airmen.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] It was now re-equipped with 24 F-86L Sabre Interceptor jets, a dedicated swept-wing interceptor which was capable of being directed to intercept targets by Ground Control Interceptor (GCI) radar stations.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The rocket-firing aircraft boasted 650 miles per hour (1,050 km/h) speed, superb maneuverability, and a 1,000-mile (1,600 km) range.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The old F-94s were shipped to other states for training purposes.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] On 1 September 1960 the unit was transferred from ADC to the Military Air Transport Service (MATS).
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The 134th exchanged its recently acquired Sabres for eight Boeing C-97 Stratofreighter aircraft.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Organizationally, the 101st Fighter Group (AD) was transferred to the Maine Air National Guard, the 157th Air Transportation Group being established by the National Guard Bureau as a new unit, replacing the 101st.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The lineage and history, however, of the 101st Fighter Group (AD) were transferred to the 157th ATS, with the 134th being redesignated as an Air Transport Squadron.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] With the transfer of the 101st to Maine, the 157th ATG became one of three groups assigned to the 133d Air Transportation Wing, Minnesota Air National Guard.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Completing the organization were the 157th Group Headquarters, the 133d Air Transport Squadron, 157th Air Base Squadron, 157th Consolidated Aircraft Maintenance Squadron, the 157th USAF Dispensary, and State Headquarters.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] On the night of 13 August 1961, the East German government erected barbed wire barriers around the 104-mile (167 km) periphery of West Berlin.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Without warning, East Berliners had been denied passage rights to the western part of the city by their own soldiers.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Kennedy federalized several Air National Guard units, including the New Hampshire Air National Guard, and the 133d ATS was placed on active duty.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Equipped with eight C-97 aircraft and manned with 675 guardsmen, the unit would stay at Grenier Field during the crisis.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] But its aircraft and crews ranged throughout the world, touching down at bases in Europe, South America, Alaska, Japan, the Philippines, and Southeast Asia.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] These missions came in addition to the ongoing ferrying of life-sustaining supplies to West Berlin.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The 157th also airlifted elements of the Turkish Army to South Korea and delivered essential communications equipment to South Vietnam.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Typical of the C-97 flights leaving Grenier AFB was one that departed in early November 1961.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Its long itinerary started with a stop at Dover AFB, Delaware, then it was on to Lajes Field, Azores; Châteauroux-Déols AB, France; Rhein-Main AB, West Germany; RAF Mildenhall, England; Keflavik Airport, Iceland; Ernest Harmon AFB, Newfoundland, and back to Grenier AFB.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] This 9,000-plus-mile flight required in excess of 40 hours of flying time and was supported by a crew of eight.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] In 11 months, the crisis cooled, and on 31 August 1962 the 900 officers and airmen of the 157th Air Transport Group were returned to State control.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] In late 1965, at the behest of the Department of Defense and in concert with other Air National Guard and Reserve units, 157th personnel joined in "Operation Christmas Star", airlifting some 23,000 pounds of gifts to United States forces in South Vietnam.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] It was a presaging of the unit's active participation in the Vietnam War which would begin in 1966.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] With all-volunteer aircrews, the three 133d ATS C-97s delivered 23,000 pounds of cargo, completely collected in New Hampshire, then shipped to Saigon and Da Nang between 26 November and 1 December.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] After Operation Christmas Star, Air National Guard support missions to South Vietnam increased.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] On 1 January 1966, the Military Air Transport Service was discontinued, being replaced by Military Airlift Command (MAC).
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] With the change of major command designations, the 157th was redesignated as the 157th Military Airlift Group, the 133d as a Military Airlift Squadron.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The 157th became part of the 21st Air Force, McGuire Air Force Base, New Jersey.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] But more dramatic than any previous change, the closure of Grenier AFB meant that the 157th was told to pack up and move to a new home at Pease AFB in Newington, New Hampshire.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The closure of Grenier AFB had been the result of Air Force-wide downsizing directed by Secretary of Defense Robert McNamara.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] At Pease AFB, the 157th was assigned to buildings on the north side of the base.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Like it or not, after 20 years on its own, the 157th was now side by side with Strategic Air Command 509th Bombardment Wing active-duty personnel.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] At the first drill in February 1966, in the confines of its hangar, the entire 700-man unit received a formal welcome by the 509th.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] During the ceremony—a reality check of sorts—base representatives explained the installation's regulations, proper wear of uniforms, and other military courtesies.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] As the unit settled into a new home, the 133d Aeromedical Evacuation flight was formed.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] It was composed of 13 flight nurses and 29 airmen serving as medical aide technicians.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Working aboard the C-97 Stratofreighter planes assigned to the 133d Military Airlift Squadron, New Hampshire medical crews were assigned to assist transporting patients from Europe and Southeast Asia.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] By March 1966, the 157th began regular logistical support for the burgeoning American forces in South Vietnam.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Each mission from New Hampshire to South Vietnam could become an air marathon of sorts.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] During one flight, the trip lasted almost 11 days, as the 133d flew from Pease AFB to Dover Air Force Base, Delaware, where cargo was loaded.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Next it was on to the West Coast, then Hawaii, Wake Island, Guam, the Philippines, and finally, South Vietnam.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] To help exhausted combat troops get their R&R, the Air National Guard, including the 157th, flew more than 110,000 military personnel throughout the U.S. and overseas.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] In the 1,352 "Combat Leave" missions logged, approximately 38,300 military personnel were transported from Southeast Asia to the states and back again.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] In December 1967, the 157th again changed aircraft, exchanging its C-97 Stratofreighters for the larger and slower C-124C Globemaster II.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The C-124 had been the cargo workhorse of the Air Force since the Korean War.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The first of the C-124s arrived on 9 February 1968.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] By late fall, the ninth and last Globemaster touched down and crew transitioning was well underway.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] By September 1969 the Group had retrained its pilots to the new aircraft and completed its first Operational Readiness Inspection as a C-124 unit, qualifying to resume global airlift support.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The 157th hauled much large "out-size" cargo such as trucks, military vehicles, and missile components.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] It also carried troops and cargo that didn't require the speedy capability of MAC's all-jet C-141 Starlifter and C-5A Galaxy airlift fleet.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Although two- and three-day flights within the U.S. were common, the 157th's overseas commitment was growing.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] In 1969 the unit transported more than 1,000 tons of cargo and 2,000 passengers, its aircrews logging 5,236 hours on 44 overseas missions to Vietnam, England, France, West Germany, Greece, Japan, Portugal, Newfoundland, Puerto Rico, and Taiwan.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] On 6 April 1971, the Secretary of the Air Force announced the redesignation of the unit to the 157th Tactical Airlift Group.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] After 10 years in the airlift business, the unit assumed a new role with its seventh type aircraft—the C-130A Hercules.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The 157th was also transferred to Tactical Air Command (TAC), with a mission to provide mobility and logistical support for ground forces in all types of operations.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] It was all part of a nationwide program involving one-third of the Air National Guard's flying units and inspired by Secretary of Defense Melvin Laird.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The C-130A was the backbone of TAC's theater airlift fleet, a medium assault transport with long range (beyond 2,000 miles), high speed (220 to 300 miles per hour), and capable of landing or taking off from a shorter runway than any comparable aircraft.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The turbo-prop aircraft with its five-man crew could carry nearly 20 tons of cargo or 92 fully equipped troops, 64 paratroops or 74 litter patients and attendants.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] On 8 July 1971 the first C-130A arrived from the 317th Tactical Airlift Wing, Lockbourne Air Force Base, Ohio.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] About a month later, on 9 August, the first C-130 flight with all-157th crew took place.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] By September heavy Phase I transition training was underway with both aircrew and support personnel at schools throughout the United States.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] By early 1972, the 133d Tactical Airlift Squadron began Phase II (combat readiness) training, and in April, low-level flying and navigational training missions were being flown day and night along air routes crossing Maine, New Hampshire, and Massachusetts.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] First drops of paratroopers and cargo began in early May, and in mid-month, the 157th passed a "no notice" Twelfth Air Force Management Effectiveness Inspection (MEI).
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] During the summer of 1973, the 157th participated in a joint Army, Air Force, and National Guard-Reserve training exercise.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Readiness Command training, code named Boldfire 1-74, was centered at Camp Joseph T.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] During Boldfire, ground personnel were airlifted aboard the unit's C-130 aircraft to Fort Campbell, Kentucky.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] They remained there throughout the exercise, maintaining aircraft.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] 157th C-130s, in turn, dropped paratroops and equipment in support of ground forces.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] During this time frame, the unit also had a crew participating in Coronet Shamrock, an Air Force-wide air-drop competition.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The 157th crew won the preliminary competition at Fort Campbell, earning the right to represent the ANG in further competition.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The operational honors were dampened somewhat on 12 October when the 133d Aeromedical Evacuation Flight was inactivated.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The 133rd AME Flight had been organized and federally recognized on 10 June 1961.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The unit's 18 officers and 27 enlisted medical personnel would fill vacancies and augment medical services in the 157th TAC Clinic.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The 1973 oil crisis caught up with the 157th at the end of 1973, and all flying activity was suspended from 22 December until 7 January 1974, due to fuel shortages throughout the country.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] In December 1974, the Group was transferred back to Military Airlift Command (MAC) when TAC's theater transport mission were transferred to MAC.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] On 1 October 1975 the 157th was relieved from Military Airlift Command and transferred to Strategic Air Command (SAC), becoming a KC-135A Stratotanker unit.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] By the end of March 1976, the New Hampshire ANG unit had largely taken over the support of the 509th Bombardment Wing from its active-duty 34th Air Refueling Squadron which was inactivated on 31 March 1976.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] By October 1976, the 157th Air Refueling Group and the 509th Bombardment Wing shared the same mission and response times, giving them a link to the "Total Force Concept".
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The 133d deployed to RAF Mildenhall, England, as part of the European Tanker Task Force.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Once in the UK, the unit engaged in friendly competition with active duty flyers in "Giant Voice".
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The 133d was also the first ANG unit to air refuel the then-experimental B-1A bomber.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] A January 1977 inspection rated the 157th SAC's first Air National Guard unit to be "fully operationally ready." It became the second ANG unit in SAC history to stand alert with the active force.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] By the end of 1978, the 157th Air Refueling Group was fully established as one of the "Best" in SAC.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] During the latter months of 1979, aircraft from the 157th joined forces with 16 KC-135A's providing air refueling support for "Crested Cap".
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] This airpower exercise tested the deployment capability of Air Force fighter aircraft moving from the U.S. to Europe in support of NATO war efforts there.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The 157th AREFG finished 1979 by winning the "Navigation" Trophy at Giant Voice '79, a four-month competition among SAC, TAC, ADTAC, ANG, AFRES, and RAF-manned bomber and air refueling tankers.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The 157th was the first Air National Guard or Air Force Reserve unit to win a trophy in the 31-year history of the SAC competition.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] During the 1980s, the 157th continued to participate in Strategic Air Command exercises like Global Shield and Giant Voice.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] In 1984, the 133d converted from its aging KC-135A fleet with new fuel efficient KC-135Es and the receipt of its first Air Force Outstanding Unit Award.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The wing engaged in routine worldwide deployments with its KC-135s, refueling a 12-aircraft tanker task force that refueled F-105s returning from a deployment in Denmark in August 1981's Operation "Coronet Rudder".
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Less than a year later, in February 1982, 160 personnel were deployed to Andersen AFB, Guam, as part of "Pacific Sentry".
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] This was the first time 133d KC-135 tankers had flown 10,000 miles in support of a mission, a unit distance record.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] During its 15 days on Guam, the unit conducted missions to Kadena AB, Okinawa, Diego Garcia, Clark AB, Philippines, Japan, and Australia.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Additionally, the 157th CES rebuilt the base fire station on Andersen AFB.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Hard, began flying the KC-135E in August 1984.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] A resident of Arlington, Massachusetts, Hard was recommended by the NHANG for pilot school at Laughlin AFB, Texas.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] She had served four years of active duty as a personnel officer at Lackland AFB, Texas, and Hanscom AFB, Massachusetts.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Hard trained on both the KC-135A and KC-135E models.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] In 1989, the first Base Realignment and Closure Commission (BRAC) recommended the closure of Pease Air Force Base.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] As part of the closure process, a Pease Redevelopment Commission (PRC) was established to plan the closure and redevelopment of the base.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] On 1 August 1999, it was resolved that the 157th Air Refueling Group, New Hampshire ANG, would remain at Pease, and the facility would be redeveloped as a civilian airport, among other planned uses by the community.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] It took only two years for the active component to complete departure activities, including transferring personnel and assets to other military installations.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The 509th's fleet of FB-111A bombers departed in phases from June to September 1990.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The 13 KC-135A tankers assigned to the 509th transferred to Wurtsmith AFB, Michigan; Plattsburgh AFB, New York; Eaker AFB, Arkansas; Carswell AFB, Texas, and Fairchild AFB, Washington. in October 1990, the personnel of the 509th were reassigned throughout the Air Force.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Pease Airport opened for civilian use through an Airfield Joint Use Agreement with the USAF on 19 July 1991.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Base Closure Law directed that the 157th ARG be consolidated into a cantonment area.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] 220 acres (89 ha) were identified and retained by the USAF for the Group's continued mission.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Having shared resources with an active-duty air base since 1966, the 157th would learn to adapt to providing all necessary functions for itself.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Base closure-related projects would eventually include an alert facility, dining hall, base security systems, fuels facilities, communications facility, magazine, and a vehicle maintenance facility.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Utility deficiencies were so severe that the program also included the complete replacement of the power and communications distribution system, and also eventually the construction of a heat plant.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] On 1 April 1991, Strategic Air Command turned control of Pease Air Force Base over to the Department of Defense, and the active military base was closed.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The remaining Air National Guard portion of the now civilian facility was renamed Pease Air National Guard Base.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Early on the morning of 7 August 1990, Operation Desert Shield, a build-up of friendly forces designed to contain the spread of Iraqi aggression, began.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] A telephone alert asked every crew member of the 133d Air Refueling Squadron to provide maximum availability so that an immediate response capability could be developed.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] All 125 Operations crew members stepped forward in voluntary support.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The unit began functioning on a 24-hour, seven-days-a-week basis.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Forty-two Desert Shield missions would be flown in the month of August as the 133d helped refuel transport aircraft and fighters heading to United States Air Forces Central (CENTAF) bases in the Middle East.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Forty volunteers were placed on full active duty status for as long as needed.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Close to 100 guard members reported during the next few days as seven additional airplanes arrived TDY from Ohio, Pennsylvania, and New Jersey ANG units, together with the 157th's own KC-135E aircraft forming an Air National Guard tanker task force.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] By 1 October, the 157th's heavy support of MAC flights in transit from the West Coast to bases in Saudi Arabia began to slow.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The 157th became one of 12 National Guard units tasked with providing refueling support to Air Force units deployed to Saudi Arabia.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] On 12 October the 157th began deployment of its assets to Saudi Arabia to form the 1709th Air Refueling Wing (Provisional) at King Abdul Aziz Air Base, Jeddah.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Personnel and aircraft, however, were dispersed at several locations in the Middle East, including Al Banteen Air Base, Abu Dhabi, United Arab Emirates; Morón Air Base, Spain; Cairo West Airport, Egypt; and other locations.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] By January 1991, the build-up of men and material in-theater was complete.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Operation Desert Storm, the attack phase of the Allied plan to liberate Kuwait and destroy Iraq's army, was ready to begin.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] With its strategic location on the Atlantic shore, the 157th mission reverted to an "Air-Bridge" mode, refueling transiting aircraft heading across the Atlantic or inbound from RAF Mildenhall, England, which served on the other end of the transatlantic route to the Middle East.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] After a short 100 hours of ground combat, Iraq's elite Republican Guard quickly collapsed, and Kuwait was easily recaptured by Coalition ground forces.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Emotional returns punctuated by parades, bands, speeches, tears, and bear-hugs were commonplace in New Hampshire as they were throughout the country.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Many deployed units returning from CENTAF bases stopped at Pease AGB on their way to their home bases.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The 157th, its aircraft festooned with yellow ribbons painted above the boom, remained in "air-bridge" mode, supporting the returning traffic.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] By late April almost everyone had come home safely.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] In July 1991, 100 Russian children from the nuclear-contaminated Chernobyl area flew into Pease to begin attending summer camps.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The Samantha Smith Foundation flight saw a Soviet Ilyushin Il-62, technically a military aircraft, land for the first time at a SAC base.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Parked just a few hundred feet away, in an ironic twist, was Air Force One.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Bush ordered the end of Alert Missions on 1 October, ending a 15-year base ritual.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] In May 1992, with the end of the Cold War, the 157th adopted the Air Force Objective Organization plan, and the unit was redesignated as the 157th Air Refueling Wing.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The 133d was assigned to the new 157th Operations Group.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] A month later, on 1 June, Strategic Air Command was inactivated as part of the Air Force reorganization after the end of the Cold War.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] It was replaced by Air Combat Command (ACC).
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] In 1993, ACC transferred its KC-135 tanker force to the new Air Mobility Command (AMC).
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] By mid-1993, the 157th was reorganizing, bringing the 157th in line with current Air Force restructuring guidelines.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The 133d's 10 KC-135E-model aircraft were replaced throughout the summer with quieter, more efficient R-models.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] With their new CFM-56 engines, a 50 percent decrease in noise resulted, and emissions were reduced 90 percent, while range, fuel off-load capability, and reliability were all increased.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] By January 1994 all the unit's KC-135's had been converted to R-Models.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The unit engaged in routine deployments and training until 1994, when the 157th began operating the Northeast Tanker Task Force together with the Maine Air National Guard.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The situation in Bosnia-Herzegovina and "Operation Deny Flight" continued to involve 157th aircraft, crews, and support personnel.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] In December, 52 unit members deployed with the Niagara Falls 107th Air Refueling Wing to Pisa Airport, Italy.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] At Pease, "Operation Phoenix Moat" missions required 157th participation to help with the flow of personnel and materiel to the area.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The mission in Bosnia was renamed "Joint Endeavor" and, finally, "Decisive Endeavor", as the crisis cooled.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Consolidating assets, the Air Guard left Istres AB, France, and operated exclusively out of Pisa, rotating units through on a month-to-month basis.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The 157th's turn came again in October 1996, as 207 unit members swapped in and out of the Italian air base for the month.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] By 1997, the 157th had already been rotating 145 members through Incirlik Air Base, Turkey, as part of "Operation Northern Watch", enforcing the no-fly zone over northern Iraq.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Three months later, in February 1998, the 157th, augmented by four transient aircraft, flew 28 sorties offloading gas to an air convoy carrying Army personnel and equipment from Georgia to the theater area.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] In the face of mounting U.S. military might, Saddam Hussein backed down.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The year 2000 saw the 157th provide support to Operation Joint Forge as well as other operational and training missions.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] During Operation Joint Forge, the 157th flew 55 sorties, off-loading over one and one half million pounds of fuel to operational fighters and surveillance aircraft off the coast of the former republic of Yugoslavia.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The 157th also provided support to the Clean Hunter 2000 NATO exercise, with a deployment to Karup Air Base, Denmark.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The 157th also deployed to fill Expeditionary Combat Support shortfalls for Operation Southern Watch and Operation Northern Watch, NORAD alert in Iceland and Alaska, support of NATO AWCS in Germany and individual rotations to Joint Forge in Istres, France.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] One such deployment involved 50 personnel in Southwest Asia during the summer, as part of an Air Expeditionary Forces deployment.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] In its 2005 BRAC Recommendations, DoD recommended to realign March Air Reserve Base, California.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The 163d Air Refueling Wing (ANG) would distribute its nine KC-135R aircraft to the 157th Air Refueling Wing (ANG), Pease Air National Guard Station (three aircraft), and several other bases.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Military judgment also placed additional force structure at Pease to support the Northeast Tanker Task Force and also robust the squadron to a more effective size of 12 aircraft.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] Following the September 11 attacks in 2001, the 157th Air Refueling Wing operated 24 hours a day, seven days a week in support of the war on terror.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] In 2009, the Wing was selected as an Active Associate Wing, bringing approximately 150 active duty members to its base.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] In August 2014, Air Force leaders announced that the 157th would become the first Air National Guard unit to equip with the Boeing KC-46 Pegasus tanker.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The Pegasus was scheduled to enter the Air Force inventory during fiscal year 2019.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] On 31 January 2019, two KC-135Rs (*58-0023* and *58-0104*) permanently departed Pease in preparation for arrival of the KC-46A later in the year.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The final KC-135 at Pease, *57-1419*, departed on 24 March 2019, for Goldwater Air National Guard Base in Phoenix, Arizona.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The first KC-46A arrived at Pease on 8 August 2019.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-group] The 12th and final KC-46A was delivered on 5 February 2021.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] The United States Air Force's **101st Intelligence Squadron** (**101 IS**), Massachusetts Air National Guard, is an intelligence unit assigned to the 102nd Intelligence Wing and located at Otis Air National Guard Base, Massachusetts.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] From its creation in 1921 to its mission change in 2008, the 101st was the mainstay of aerospace defence for the Northeastern United States.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] The 101st was deployed during the Berlin Crisis to France and was also deployed to Panama during Operation Coronet Nighthawk.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] It also participated in Operation Northern Watch.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] During the September 11 attacks, the 101st was the first Air Force unit to send aircraft toward New York City, but they arrived too late to help stop the attacks.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] Base downsizing through the Base Realignment and Closure (BRAC) process removed the wing's F-15C Eagles beginning in 2007, leaving the 101st with an intelligence gathering mission that will be fully active starting in 2010.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] It is one of three Air National Guard wings that works with the Air Force Intelligence, Surveillance and Reconnaissance Agency.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] The squadron has its origins at Kelly Field, Texas, being organized as the **101st Aero Squadron** on 22 August 1918.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] The personnel were composed of new recruits from various Recruit Barracks, including Fort McDowell, Vancouver Barracks, Fort Sam Houston, Columbus Barracks, Fort Williams, Fort Warren and Fort Oglethorpe.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] During September 1917, it was found necessary to transfer many of its men.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] Altogether, 113 men were transferred out and 32 transferred in, leaving the squadron well below its authorized strength.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] In October, the squadron was again filled up to a required total of 150 recruits.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] After basic indoctrination into the military, on 29 October, the squadron was ordered to overseas service, being ordered to report to the Aviation Concentration Center, Garden City, Long Island.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] A wave of measles and mumps plagued the squadron, and it was placed in the Quarantine barracks for several weeks.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] It received orders to report to the Port of Entry, Philadelphia for immediate transport to France in mid-December 1917, sailing on the SS Northland on 4 December.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] It arrived in Liverpool, England on Christmas Day, after spending a week at Halifax, Nova Scotia, waiting to form up with a convoy for the cross-Atlantic voyage.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] After a few days at a Rest Camp near Winchester, England, the squadron moved to Le Havre, France and then traveled by train to the Replacement Concentration Center, AEF, St.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] Maixent Replacement Barracks, France, arriving on 1 January 1918.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] Maixent, the 101st was re-organized according to the vocations of the men.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] As a consequence, many changes were made with transfers in and out of the squadron.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] It was designated as a *Service Squadron*, and assigned to the 3d Aviation Instruction Center (3d AIC), Issoudun Aerodrome.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] It was assigned to the main field initially, before being moved to Field Five to take up the duties of the Engineering department.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] Its primary duty became the repairing and maintaining the conditions of the planes used in the instructional classes, primarily French Nieuports.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] The squadron remained at 3d AIC until after the Armistice with Germany in November 1918, then returned to the United States in early April 1918.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] Arrived at Michel Field where the squadron members were demobilized and returned to civilian life.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] After World War I ended, there was a general interest in organizing aviation assets for the National Guard system.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] At the time, in the US force structure aircraft were organized into infantry units in a fashion similar to other weapons, like artillery.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] Guard units without their own aircraft units would need units from other forces to be sent to operate with them, a situation no-one thought was promising.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] In Massachusetts, the Archie Club, composed of former Army Air Service pilots, lobbied for the formation of an air unit for the Massachusetts National Guard.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] The state had earlier been allotted the entire 26th Guard Division.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] The 101st built its own air base on land-filled tidal flats at Jeffries Point, East Boston.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] The 101 flew its Curtiss JN-4 "Jenny" aircraft throughout New England at air shows, county fairs and other events.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] In addition, the 101st attended two-week summer camps that simulated forward deployments.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] Pilots flew their Curtiss O-11s to temporary fields on Cape Cod while ground crews followed in trucks.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] One of these fields became Cape Cod Airfield.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] In 1933 Jeffery Field was rebuilt with new hangars and administrative buildings, and renamed Logan Airport in honor of Major General Edward L.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] Logan, who commanded the 26th Division from 1923 to 1928.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] The 101st helped gain fame when it played a big part in the U.S.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] Army Air Service's flight around the world.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] Louis* when Charles Lindbergh visited the state.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] On 11 January 1937, 2nd Lieutenant Frank Otis died when his Douglas O-46A crashed into the Illinois River.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] As a result, Otis Field was named for him in 1938.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] In 1940, the 101st was separated from the 26th Infantry Division.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] On 31 July 1941, when it was then moved from Logan to Otis Field at Camp Edwards.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] Otis Field was named after 1st Lt Frank J.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] On 20 May 1944, had its mission changed when it was re designated as the 39th Photo Reconnaissance Squadron.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] It was then placed under the command of the Ninth Air Force and deployed to the European Theater in December 1944.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] The 39th returned to the states in August 1945 and was redesignated as the 101st Fighter Squadron in May 1946, and then inactivated two months later.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] Veterans of the 101st and Army Air Force reorganized the 101st at Logan Airport on 29 July 1946.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] In the post-war era the National Guard Bureau began a major expansion of its air units.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] Massachusetts was allotted the 67th Fighter Wing, which was assigned to Air Defense Command.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] With the formation of the US Air Force the Guard units suffered from neglect.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] In the midst of the switch to jet fighters, the Guard units were left with their handed-down and generally overused World War II propeller aircraft, and had little money for training.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] As the Cold War intensified, the Air Forced looked to the Guard to fill US-based interception missions and started overhauling their organization.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] On 1 November 1950 the 67th Fighter Wing was inactivated and replaced by the 102nd Fighter Wing, including just the 101st and 131st along with their associated support units.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] The squadrons were issued F-84B Thunderjets, but these aircraft were recalled and replaced by F-51 Mustangs which were flown until 1954 when the F-94 Starfire replaced the Twin Mustangs.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] In 1952 the 253d Combat Communications Group was activated and added to the 102nd.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] In 1958 the Wing converted to the F-86H Sabre.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] From 1956 to 1976, the 102d was headed by Brigadier General Charles W.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] Sweeney, who piloted the Boeing B-29 Superfortress, which dropped the Fat Man atomic bomb on Nagasaki, Japan in 1945.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] During the summer of 1961, as the Berlin Crisis unfolded, several USAF reserve units were notified on 16 August of their pending recall to active duty.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] On 1 October, the Massachusetts Air National Guard's 102nd Tactical Fighter Wing and its three squadrons, the 101st Tactical Fighter Squadron, the 131st Tactical Fighter Squadron, and the 138th Tactical Fighter Squadron went on active duty at Otis Air Force Base.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] Between 28 and 30 October, the 101st TFS departed Logan International Airport to Phalsbourg, France.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] The wing deployed 82 Sabres across the Atlantic.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] In addition two C-47 Skytrains and six T-33 Shooting Star aircraft were assigned to the wing for support and training purposes.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] The 101st's primary mission at the time was to provide close air support to NATO ground forces and air interdiction.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] Starting on 5 December, the 102nd began deploying to Wheelus Air Base, Libya for gunnery training.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] During its time in Europe, the 101st participated in several USAF and NATO exercises, including a deployment to Leck Air Base, West Germany near the Danish border.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] At Leck, ground and support crews from both countries exchanged duties, learning how to perform aircraft maintenance and operational support tasks.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] On 7 May 1962, the Seventeenth Air Force stated that the 102nd would deploy back to the United States during the summer, returning in July 1962.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] Regular USAF personnel, along with a group of ANG personnel who volunteered to remain on active duty formed the 480th Tactical Fighter Squadron of the newly activated 366th Tactical Fighter Wing.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] In 1968, the 102nd Tactical Fighter Wing moved to Otis Air Force Base.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] The next year the squadron was reassigned from Air Defense Command to Tactical Air Command.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] The wing flew the F-84F Thunderstreak from 1964 until June 1971, when a squadron of F-100D Super Sabres was transferred directly from units fighting the Vietnam War.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] After making the transition to the "Hun," the Mach 2 F-106 Delta Darts soon arrived to replace them.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] On 10 June 1972, after completing the move to the F-106, the unit officially became the 102nd Fighter Interceptor Squadron.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] The squadron participated in the interception of Soviet TU-95 Bear bombers on many occasions, the first of which occurred off Long Island in 1975.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] Many of these occasions included escorting the aircraft to Cuba.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] Other escort missions involved the escorting of drug smuggling planes and the identifying of one mysterious ghost plane, which turned out later to be a weather balloon.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] The 102nd FIW retired its F-106s on 5 January 1988.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] Between January and April 1988, the squadron converted to the F-15A Eagle, which it received from a unit inactivating at Minot Air Force Base.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] It then resumed its alert commitment at Otis, and also provided an alert detachment at Loring AFB.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] The 101st was the first ANG air defense unit to be equipped with the F-15.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] The squadron continued its air defense mission after the fall of the Soviet Union.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] With the reorganization of the USAF in 1992, the wing was reassigned from the disbanding Tactical Air Command to the new Air Combat Command.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] On 11 September 2001, two planes were hijacked and flown towards New York City.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] Then Federal Aviation Administration contacted the North American Aerospace Defense Command's Northeast Air Defense Sector at Rome, New York, bypassing standard procedures.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] NORAD ordered the 101st Fighter Squadron to scramble its jets.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] Two F-15s piloted by Lieutenant Colonel Timothy Duffy and Major Daniel Nash were scrambled and took off to fly to New York.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] Difficulties in pinpointing the exact location of Flight 11 led to a delay of five minutes before the scramble order was given at 8:43.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] When Flight 11 hit the North Tower at 8:46, the two F-15 Eagles that had been ordered to scramble were still on the runway at Otis; they did not take to the air until 8:52.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] Lacking a target, the F-15s were directed to airspace off the Long Island coast.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] Uncertain about what to do, the planes were ordered to 'hold as needed' there.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] At 9:02, Flight 175 hit the South Tower while the fighters flew to their holding position.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] The Northeast Air Defense Sector was not contacted about this hijacked plane until 9:03.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] From 9:09 to 9:13 the F-15s stayed in the holding pattern.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] At 9:13, the pilots of the F-15s told FAA Boston Center that they were heading for Manhattan to establish a Combat Air Patrol (CAP) over the area.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] The F-15s arrived over Manhattan at 9:25.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] More than 600 wing members were mobilized for Operation Noble Eagle at different times.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] The wing never deployed overseas to support the wars in Afghanistan and Iraq but it did continue to patrol the Northeastern United States skies.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] The wing converted from the F-15A/B to the F-15C/D in 2004.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] The BRAC 2005 commission originally planned to close Otis Air National Guard Base and dissolve the 101st.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] Locals argued that this would leave a huge gap in the national air defenses.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] BRAC officials, after visiting the base, decided to keep it open, but the 101st would still lose its planes, only this time they were only going to the 104th Fighter Wing, based at Barnes Municipal Airport, near the town of Westfield in western Massachusetts.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] The wing hosted its last airshow with the F-15C Eagle at the end of Air Force Week in August 2007.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] The wing shared a commonality with the 101st Air Refueling Wing, the 103d Fighter Wing, and the 104th Fighter Wing, which due to BRAC decisions, also changed the type of planes that they flew.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] Beginning in 2007, the F-15s began moving to Barnes Municipal Airport.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] With the grounding of the F-15 Eagles, the 158th Fighter Wing, which is based in Vermont temporarily took over the role of patrolling the Northeast's skies.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] This interruption of the F-15's flight, coinciding with the transitioning of the fighter jets to the 104th Fighter Wing, created some issues.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] The move was originally scheduled to be completed at the end of January, but the grounding of the F-15's in late 2007 and early 2008 delayed this move to the end of February.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] On 24 January 2008, the 101st Fighter Squadron flew its last patrol mission.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] The unit's wing commander, Colonel Anthony Schiavi, led the flight, accompanied by Major Daniel Nash, who was one of the first responders for 9/11.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] Fire trucks were on hand when the team landed a half-hour later, giving the planes and the pilots the customary ceremonial hose-down for the last time.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] As soon as it was announced that the wing would be kept alive and Otis Air National Guard Base would remain open, the state government began thinking of the future for the 101st.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] There was talk among the members of the Massachusetts National Guard that it could transition to an intelligence mission so that it could help support the war on terror.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] The plans hit a roadblock when it was announced that there were few funds left with which the wing could use to transition into its new mission.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] The new mission was finally confirmed when Governor Deval Patrick announced that the wing would transition to an intelligence mission as soon as the planes left.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] Original BRAC plans only said that a Distributed Common Ground System would be created at Otis.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] These plans didn't include the air guardsmen affected by the loss of their jobs.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] The issue was finally resolved when the Air Force announced its plans, right before the F-15's started to leave for Barnes.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] On 1 April 2008, the 101st Fighter Squadron was re-designated as the 101st Intelligence Squadron, with a formal ceremony on 6 April.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] The wing will reach full operation in 2010.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] By 1 October, the wing is expected to be operationally ready.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] During the time preceding the wing reaching full operational capacity, members of the wing had the option of moving with the F-15s to Barnes.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] Most members decided to stay behind and train for their new missions.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] The crash trucks moved with the F-15s to Barnes, leaving the brush breakers of the Massachusetts Military Reservation behind.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] The buildings formerly occupied by the planes will be reused for the intelligence mission by wing members.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-fighter-squadron] These buildings include the hangars that the F-15s formerly occupied.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-rescue-squadron] The **101st Rescue Squadron (101 RQS)** is a unit of the New York Air National Guard 106th Rescue Wing stationed at Francis S.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-rescue-squadron] Gabreski Air National Guard Base, Westhampton Beach, New York.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-rescue-squadron] The squadron is equipped with the Sikorsky HH-60G Pave Hawk and HH-60W Jolly Green II helicopters, configured for combat search and rescue operations.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-rescue-squadron] Established in 2004 by the Air Force Special Operations Command as part of a re-organization of Air National Guard rescue wings which created separate squadrons for fixed-wing, helicopter and pararescue elements of the 106th Rescue Wing.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-rescue-squadron] Subsequently reverted to Air Combat Command.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-rescue-squadron] The squadron maintains, supports and operates the Sikorsky HH-60G Pave Hawk and HH-60W Jolly Green II helicopters of the 106th Rescue Wing.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-rescue-squadron] It is an integral component of the 106th Operations Group, along with the Lockheed HC-130J Combat King II search and rescue/aerial refueling aircraft of the 102d Rescue Squadron, transporting pararescue personnel of the 103d RQS in their mission.
[src:air-national-guard/101st-rescue-squadron] For the history of the squadron prior to 2004, see 102nd Rescue Squadron.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] The **Air National Guard** (**ANG**), also known as the **Air Guard**, is a federal military reserve force of the United States Air Force (USAF), as well as the "air militia" of each U.S. state, the District of Columbia, the Commonwealth of Puerto Rico, and the territories of Guam and the U.S.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] It, along with the Army National Guard component of each state, district, commonwealth or territory, makes up the National Guard of each region as applicable.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] The ANG and the United States Air Force Reserve constitute the two air reserve components of the USAF.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] When Air National Guard units are used under the jurisdiction of the state governor they are fulfilling their militia role.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] When federalized by order of the president of the United States, ANG units become an active part of the U.S.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] They are jointly administered by the states and the National Guard Bureau, a joint bureau of the Army and Air Force that oversees the U.S.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] The modern day National Guard in the U.S. traces its origins to 13 December 1636, when the Massachusetts Bay Colony's General Court passed an act calling for the creation of three regiments, organizing existing separate militia companies in and around Boston.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] The creation of the militia regiments was caused by the perceived need to defend the Bay Colony against American Indians and from other European countries operating in North America.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] This organization formed the basis of subsequent colonial and, post-independence, state and territorial militias which later became the Army National Guard.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Being "local" ground forces affiliated with the Army, militias were considered state-centric/territorial-centric in nature, this versus naval forces, which were considered wholly activities of the federal government.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] This distinction accounts for why there are no National Guard components in the U.S.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Army, it was only natural that a separate Air National Guard would be established with the divestiture of the former U.S.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Army Air Forces and its establishment as a separate and independent U.S.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] The Air National Guard was officially established in law as a separate reserve component on 18 September 1947, concurrent with the establishment of the U.S.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] However, National Guard aviation emerged before World War I with aviation units in Army National Guard organizations.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] In April 1908, a group of enthusiasts organized an "aeronautical corps" at the Park Avenue Armory in New York City to learn ballooning.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] They were members of the 1st Company, Signal Corps, New York National Guard.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Although they received instruction and assembled a balloon, it was not clear whether members of the unit had ever actually ascended in it.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] In 1910 the unit raised $500 to finance its first aircraft.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] During the Mexican Border Crisis of 1915 Captain Raynal Cawthorne Bolling organized and took command of a unit that became the **1st Aero Company, New York National Guard**.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] It trained at Mineola Field, Mineola, Long Island.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] It is recognized as the ANG's oldest unit and its lineage is carried by the 102nd Rescue Squadron of the New York Air National Guard.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] On 13 July 1916, the 1st Aero Company mobilized during the border crisis with Mexico. the unit was called into federal service when the Mexican revolution spilled over the border into the United States.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Bolling's unit was joined at Mineola by the 2nd Aero Company of Buffalo and 12 Guard officers from other states.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Both air units remained at Mineola during the crisis.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] When the U.S. entered World War I in April 1917, the War Department decided that it would not mobilize National Guard air units.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Instead, individual Guard volunteers provided a major pool for the Army to draw aviators from.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] They were required to leave the Guard and enter the Signal Corps Reserve if they wished to fly in the war.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] About 100 National Guard pilots joined the newly formed U.S.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Guardsmen also played prominent roles in air operations in France.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] On 14 April 1918, Tennessee guardsman Reed Chambers flew with Eddie Rickenbacker and David Peterson of the 94th Pursuit Squadron from Villeneuve, France on the first combat mission ever ordered by an American commander of a U.S. squadron of American pilots.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] At least four guardsmen—Chambers, Field Kindley (Kansas), Reed Landis (Illinois), and Martinus Stenseth (Minnesota) – became aces.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Bleckley of Kansas was awarded the Medal of Honor posthumously for his heroism as an aerial observer.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] After the armistice and the return of the American Expeditionary Force in 1919, the wartime squadrons were demobilized and inactivated.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] After the war, National Guard aviation was placed on a permanent basis over the initial opposition of the Army's General Staff.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] In 1920, the Militia Bureau and the Army Air Service agreed on a plan for re-organizing National Guard aviation units.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] On 17 January 1921, the 109th Observation Squadron of the Minnesota National Guard (1921–1941) became the first post World War I air unit to receive federal recognition.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] During the interwar period, 29 observation squadrons were established.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] They were either integral elements of National Guard infantry divisions or assigned to Army corps aviation.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] An aviator in the 110th Observation Squadron of the Missouri National Guard (1923–1943) became the most famous National Guard pilot during the interwar period: Captain Charles A.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] His service illustrated the close ties between military and commercial aviation.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Trained to fly by the Army, he joined the 110th Observation Squadron in November 1925.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] The following year, he became chief pilot for an airmail venture started by fellow 110th pilots Major William Robertson and his brother Frank.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] After Lindbergh made his historic solo trans-Atlantic flight in May 1927, he recalled his service in the Guard fondly.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] After the Fall of France, during 1940–1941, approximately 4,800 experienced National Guard aviation personnel were mobilized from their observation squadrons.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] They provided a significant augmentation of the Army's rapidly expanding air arm during a critical period.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Most Guard air units were stripped of many key personnel, and the units were federalized into the regular Army Air Corps and were re-equipped with more modern aircraft.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Some of the early-deploying squadrons maintained a degree of unit integrity and cohesion.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] But, most lost their character and identity as Guard organizations during World War II.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] The units were transformed from observation organizations into reconnaissance, liaison, fighter, and bombardment squadrons.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] They served in every major combat theater during the war.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] The most significant wartime contribution of National Guard aviators was to train and lead the large numbers of volunteer airmen who had entered the AAF.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] That role was epitomized by Lt Col Addison E.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] On 1 August 1943, Baker commanded the VIII Bomber Command's 93rd Bombardment Group on a daring but ill-fated low-level attack against enemy oil refineries at Ploiești, Romania.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Baker was posthumously awarded the Medal of Honor for his heroic leadership.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] The Air National Guard as it exists today, a separate reserve component of the United States Air Force in addition to the purely "federal" Air Force Reserve, was a product of the politics of postwar planning and inter-service rivalry during World War II.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] The Army Air Forces leaders who planned and maneuvered for an independent postwar Air Force during World War II had little confidence in the reserves of the U.S.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Army, especially the state-dominated National Guard.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] On the contrary, those leaders expected to build the largest and most modern standing air force possible.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] However, domestic politics and American history forced them to significantly alter their plans.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Determined to include an Air Force National Guard in the postwar U.S. military establishment during World War II, the National Guard Association of the United States flexed its considerable political muscle.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Army Air Forces (USAAF) to plan for a significant Air Force National Guard once the overseas fighting ended.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Marshall, the Army chief of staff, also pressured the USAAF to revise its ambitious plans for a large postwar active duty force.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Truman instituted dramatic postwar military budget cuts, he split defense dollars evenly among the Army, Navy, and Air Force.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] That move also required the Air Force to plan for a far smaller active duty service than it had envisaged.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] As a result, the Air Force needed both reserve components, the Air National Guard and the Air Force Reserve, to help fill the gap.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] As the wartime Army Air Forces demobilized in 1945 and 1946, inactivated unit designations were allotted and transferred to various State and Territorial Air National Guard bureaus to provide them unit designations to re-establish them as Air National Guard units.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Initially, the National Guard Bureau (NGB) developed a table of organization for the Air National Guard to include at least one unit allocation per state.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] The territories of Alaska, Hawaii and Puerto Rico were allocated one unit designation each.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] A table of organization was developed in which a series of twelve ANG Wings were allocated to provide command and control over separate regions of the United States.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Each Wing controlled three or four Groups within the region.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] The Groups controlled squadrons within the region, sometimes distributed over several states.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] On 21 August 1946, inactivated USAAF group and squadron designations were transferred from the Department of the Army to the National Guard Bureau.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] The units were re-designated with unit designations within the 101–299 range and allotments were made to Adjutant General of the states and territories whose mission it was to organize the units being allocated and prepare them for federal recognition by the NGB.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] The combat element was organized into twelve wings which were then divided into 20 fighter groups totaling 62 squadrons, two light bombardment groups comprising four squadrons, and five composite groups with twelve fighter squadrons and six bombardment squadrons.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Individual state squadrons were assigned to either Groups or Wings, depending on circumstances, allocations, and gaining commands of the Army Air Forces.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] As individual units were organized, federally recognized, and activated, the Army Air Forces provided them airfields, equipment and surplus aircraft.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Once formed, the units began obtaining federal recognition, and the state Air National Guard units were established.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Its primary units were 84 flying squadrons, mostly equipped with P-51 Mustang and P-47 Thunderbolt fighters with air defense of the continental United States as their main mission, its units under the jurisdiction of the USAAF Air Defense Command.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Tactical Air Command also had several ANG units being assigned B-26 Invader medium bombers.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] 18 September 1947, however, is considered the Air National Guard's official birth, concurrent with the establishment of the United States Air Force as a separate branch of the United States military under the National Security Act.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] The postwar Air National Guard force of the late 1940s included 58,000 members.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Between 1946 and 1949, all of the initial allotment of units received federal recognition in the CONUS.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] The Hawaii Territory ANG received recognition and was activated on 4 November 1946; the Puerto Rico ANG on 23 November 1947, and the Alaska Territory ANG on 15 September 1952.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] At the end of October 1950, the Air National Guard converted to the wing-base (Hobson Plan) organization.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] As a result, the former Army Air Forces Wings which were allocated were inactivated by the National Guard Bureau returned to the control of the Department of the Air Force on 31 October 1950.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] The personnel and equipment of the inactivated wings were transferred to new Air National Guard wings which were established, recognized and activated on 1 November 1950.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] After World War II, the Air National Guard developed an unfortunate reputation as a glorified "flying club" for World War II combat veterans.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Not only did the units and individuals lack specific wartime missions, their equipment, especially aircraft, was obsolete and their training was usually deplorable.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Once mobilized, those air national guardsmen proved to be almost totally unprepared for combat.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Regardless of their previous training and equipment, Air National Guard units were assigned almost at random to major air commands.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] It took months and months for ANG units to become combat ready; some units never succeeded.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] During the Korean War, some 45,000 air guardsmen, 80 percent of the force, were mobilized.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] That callup exposed the weaknesses of the United States' various military reserve programs, including the ANG.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Sixty-six of the Air Guard's ninety-two flying squadrons, along with numerous support units, were mobilized.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Once in federal service, they proved to be unprepared for combat.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Many key air guardsmen were used as fillers elsewhere in the Air Force.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] It took three to six months for some ANG units to become combat ready.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Eventually, they made substantial contributions to the war effort and the Air Force's global buildup.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] In the Far East, the ANG's 136th and 116th Fighter-Bomber Wings compiled excellent combat records flying F-84 Thunderjets.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Air guardsmen flew 39,530 combat sorties and destroyed 39 enemy aircraft.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] But, 101 of them were either killed or declared missing in action during the conflict.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Four air guardsmen—captains Robert Love (California), Clifford D.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Jolley (Utah), and Robinson Risner (Oklahoma), plus Major James Hagerstrom (Texas) – became aces, with some, such as Risner, later transferring to the Regular Air Force.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Largely as a result of the Korean War experience, senior ANG and Air Force leaders became seriously committed to building the Air National Guard as an effective reserve component.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] With the reinforcement of the Far East Air Forces (FEAF), Air National Guard squadrons were deployed to Europe in late 1950, being assigned to newly constructed bases in France as part of United States Air Forces in Europe (USAFE).
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] These deployments helped reinforce the NATO commitment of the United States in case the combat in Korea became part of a wider conflict with the Soviet Union.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Beginning in February 1951, mobilized units were assigned to Air Defense Command (ADC), Strategic Air Command (SAC) and Tactical Air Command (TAC), replacing or augmenting active duty units.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Air national guardsmen assigned to ADC also were assigned to aircraft control and warning as well as radar calibration units.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Their organizations either strengthened American air defenses or were converted to tactical air control units that directed Air Force fighter aircraft in the continental United States, Alaska, Newfoundland, Europe, and French Morocco.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] As a result of the federalization of the Air National Guard, ADC, SAC and TAC established additional wings for command and control of the federalized units.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Air national guardsmen began to be demobilized in July 1952, with their units being inactivated by the active duty air force.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Subsequently, the individual state Air National Guard bureaus reactivated and reformed the units beginning in January 1953.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] The USAF-established wings were also allocated to their states.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Although Korean War hostilities ended in July 1953, the Cold War with the Soviet Union persisted.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] The initial mobilization fiasco forced the Air Force to achieve an accommodation with the Air National Guard and to thoroughly revamp its entire reserve system.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Because of the problems associated with the Korean War mobilizations, the Air Force and its reserve components pioneered new approaches like the runway alert program to reserve training and management.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] The Air Division chief at the National Guard Bureau wanted to find an innovative way to provide additional training for fighter pilots after their units were demobilized.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] At the same time, Air Defense Command could not call upon sufficient active duty Air Force units to defend the continental United States against the Soviet air threat.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] It was proposed to employ ANG pilots full-time from "strategically placed" Air National Guard units to perform "air intercept missions" against unidentified aircraft entering United States airspace.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Using air national guardsmen from the 138th Fighter-Interceptor Squadron at Hancock Field, Syracuse, New York, and the 194th Fighter-Bomber Squadron at Hayward, California, the experiment began on 1 March 1953.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] It proved a great success and in August eight squadrons began "standing alert" using volunteer aircrews on a rotating basis for 14 hours a day.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] In October, nine more squadrons joined the program.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] The ANG runway alert program required some planes and pilots to be available around-the-clock to become airborne within minutes of being notified to scramble.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] At its peak in the mid-1950s, all 70 Air National Guard fighter squadrons participated in that program.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] That number was reduced to 25 by 1961 due to budget constraints.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Most of the runway alert exercises involved interceptions of SAC bombers.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] A few actual scrambles turned out to be interceptions of late or off-course commercial airliners.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] The runway alert experiment in 1953 marked the beginning of the Air National Guard's modern homeland defense role.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] It was the first broad effort to integrate reserve units into a major Air Force combat mission in peacetime on a continuing basis using volunteers.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Originally the Air National Guard was designed as a combat reserve force.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] After World War II, its flying units consisted of 72 fighter and 12 light bomber squadrons equipped with obsolescent World War II propeller-driven aircraft while the active duty Air Force transitioned to jet fighters.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Although it had no airlift or tanker units, the Air National Guard's flying units were equipped with a small number of liaison, trainer, and transport planes, and the Air National Guard actively sought out new missions and aircraft.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] With the end of World War II, the Air Force dropped "Air Commando" or special operations units from its rolls, although they were revived for the Korean War.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] After that conflict, in April 1955, the Air National Guard acquired its first special operations unit when the 129th Air Resupply Squadron was federally recognized and two C-46 Commandos were delivered to it at Hayward, California.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] As its P-51 Mustangs and P-47 Thunderbolts became more and more obsolescent in the jet age of the 1950s, the force structure gradually changed to include a significant number of airlift, tanker, and specialized combat-support units.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] As the Air National Guard expanded, additional squadrons, including airlift units as well as Air Resupply and Communications units, were established.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Additional command and control groups and wings were also established by the National Guard Bureau and allocated to the states.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] The ANG however, unlike the active duty USAF, did not inactivate its combat groups during the 1950s as part of the tri-deputate organization.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Many of the combat groups remained assigned to the wings from which they were derived.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] It was not until 1974 that the ANG fully adapted the USAF tri-deputate organization and inactivated its combat groups, assigning its operational squadrons directly to the wings.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] The Air National Guard aggressively worked to preserve its existing flying units by obtaining the most modern aircraft available.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Some existing Air National Guard fighter units equipped with piston-driven fighters, however, could not convert to jets because the runways at the local airports where they were based were too short.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] In addition, some local leaders simply did not want jet fighters operating in their communities.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] The ANG considered replacing the fighter squadrons in these instances with transport aircraft a viable option for overcoming runway issues or community objections and also was a way to keep experienced senior aviators in the cockpit.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] During the late 1950s, the Air Force allowed several Air National Guard units to trade in their aging piston-driven fighters for second-line transports.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] New Jersey's newly organized 150th Air Transport Squadron (Light) became the first pure airlift unit in the Air National Guard on 1 February 1956.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Two other aeromedical transport squadrons followed that year, primarily because of the impracticality of converting their locations to modern jet fighter operations.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] In 1959, the Air Force, in order to save operating funds, planned to phase out 48 C-97 Stratofreighters before their replacements were available to the active force.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] The Air National Guard requested these aircraft be sent to ANG units, and in January 1960, units in California, Minnesota, New Hampshire, New York, and Oklahoma began trading in their obsolete fighters for C-97s.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Additionally, the Air National Guard also took on an air refueling mission.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] The Air National Guard received its first KC-97 Stratofreighter aerial tankers in July and August 1961.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] During that period, the 108th Fighter-Interceptor Squadron in Illinois, the 126th Fighter-Interceptor Squadron in Wisconsin, and the 145th Air Transport Squadron in Ohio, converted to KC-97Fs and were redesignated air refueling squadrons.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] World War II had left the city of Berlin 100 miles deep within East German territory, controlled by the Soviet Union, and divided into Soviet, British, French, and United States zones of occupation, administered under local agreements which did not guarantee Western access to the city.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Responding to a series of Soviet actions in 1948, the three western allies consolidated their zones and formed the city of West Berlin.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] For fifteen years the western powers maintained a tenacious hold on West Berlin under periodic harassment of the Soviets.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] On 13 August 1961, Berliners woke up to find they lived in a divided city.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] A wall now separated East Berlin from West Berlin.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] With that provocative act, the Soviet Union ratcheted up the Cold War.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Kennedy mobilized a limited number of Reserve and Guard units, dispatching 11 ANG fighter squadrons to Europe.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] All the Guard units were in place within a month of their respective mobilization days, although they required additional training, equipment, and personnel after being called up.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] In all, some 21,000 air guardsmen were mobilized during the 1961 Berlin Crisis.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] By August 1962, the units mobilized for the Berlin Crisis returned to state control.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] They had hardly resumed normal operations when President Kennedy announced on 22 October 1962 that the Soviet Union had placed nuclear warheads in Cuba, only 90 miles from Florida.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] With the Cuban Missile Crisis, Air National Guard fighter units trained for "no notice" deployments, and volunteer ANG airlift crews and their aircraft augmented Air Force global airlift operations.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Air National Guard bases hosted Air Force fighters and bombers dispersed there to avoid a possible Soviet nuclear response to the crisis.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] But in the end, no ANG unit was federalized.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] As a result of these two Cold War incidents, from January through December 1963, for the first time Air National Guard airlift units began routinely deploying overseas during their annual training periods, primarily to Europe, to exercise their wartime missions.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Air National Guard transport units hauled cargo for the Military Air Transport Service (MATS) while training for their wartime global airlift role.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] The Texas Air National Guard's 136th Air Refueling Wing inaugurated Operation Creek Party on 1 May 1967, because the Regular Air Force did not have enough KC-135 Stratotanker aircraft available in Europe to train its fighter pilots in USAFE.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] The operation eventually involved nine ANG air refueling groups that rotated approximately every two weeks to Rhein-Main Air Base in West Germany.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] The Vietnam War provided the next significant test for the Air National Guard.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] However, for largely domestic political reasons, President Lyndon B.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Johnson chose not to mobilize most of the nation's reserve forces before 1968.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] His reasons for not mobilizing reserve forces were many.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Primarily, he did not believe that the war in Vietnam justified the dramatic act of mobilizing Reserve and National Guard forces.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] He accepted the need to fight the war, but he wanted to prosecute it as quietly as possible, not attracting too much attention at home and risk jeopardizing his domestic programs.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] He also wanted to avoid drawing the Communist Chinese into the war or the attention of the Soviet Union, the latter which might view the mobilization of Reserve and National Guard units as "escalatory" within a larger Cold War context.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Air National Guard airlift units, however, began flying regularly to Japan and South Vietnam beginning in 1966 to support Military Airlift Command (MAC) operations.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] These flights continued on a regular basis until 1972.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] In addition, between August 1965 and September 1969, Air National Guard domestic and offshore aeromedical evacuation flights freed active duty Air Force resources for such missions in Southeast Asia (SEA).
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Moreover, after the 1968 Tet Offensive in which the Communist North Vietnamese and Vietcong troops attacked positions throughout the Republic of Vietnam, the Pentagon dispatched four Air National Guard fighter squadrons to that nation.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] In addition, the Pueblo Crisis in Korea also saw mobilized air force reservists, air national guardsmen and naval reservists in flying units.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] That crisis prompted the third partial Air National Guard mobilization since the end of World War II, and eventually two ANG fighter squadrons were dispatched to South Korea.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] However, the Pueblo crisis ended without a resort to combat.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] In July 1970, two EC-121 "Super Constellations" from the Pennsylvania ANG's 193rd Tactical Electronic Warfare Squadron departed their home station for Korat RTAFB, Thailand.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] The 355th Tactical Fighter Squadron (355th TFS) in 1967 was a Regular Air Force squadron assigned to the 354th Tactical Fighter Wing at Myrtle Beach AFB, South Carolina.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] The 355th deployed on temporary duty (TDY) to Phù Cát Air Base on 14 May 1968 with 13 of its 30 pilots being ANG members.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] The transfer became permanent on 26 June 1968, at which time all TDY members were offered the opportunity to volunteer for a full year's tour.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] All 13 ANG pilots volunteered, one of whom was killed in action a month later.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] By Christmas 1968, 87% of the squadron's support personnel were ANG members.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Five of the ANG pilots also volunteered as *Misty* Forward Air Controllers (FACs) flying the F-100 Super Sabre.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] In all, ANG pilots were awarded 23 Silver Stars, 47 Distinguished Flying Crosses, and 46 Bronze Stars with Combat V for valor while stationed at Phu Cat.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] The concept sought to strengthen and rebuild public confidence in the reserve forces while saving money by reducing the size of the active duty force.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] The policy also insured that reservists and guardsmen, not draftees, would be the first and primary source of manpower to augment the active duty forces in any future crisis.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] With the active forces being reduced after the end of the Vietnam War, a significant number of older C-130A Hercules tactical airlifters became available for the Air National Guard and Air Force Reserve, which allowed the Korean War-era C-119 Flying Boxcars and C-124 Globemasters to be retired.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] However, the Total Force Concept led to pressure to upgrade the reserve forces to front-line aircraft and beginning in 1974, new Ling-Temco-Vought (LTV) A-7D Corsair II ground attack aircraft began to be sent to Air National Guard units directly from the LTV manufacturing plant in Dallas.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] As A-10 Thunderbolt IIs began to replace the A-7Ds in the Regular Air Force in the mid and late 1970s, additional A-7D aircraft were transferred to the ANG.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] F-4 Phantom IIs began to be received by the ANG in the late 1970s with the F-15A Eagle and F-16A Fighting Falcons coming into the active inventory and ANG's F-100 Super Sabres being retired.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Starting in 1975, the ANG began conducting operations in Latin America and by the late 1970s to defend the Panama Canal and to provide training support, embassy resupply, search and rescue, and counterdrug operations.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] In addition, the ANG airlifted supplies and hardware to remote radar sites and performed aerial mapping operations.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] In June 1979, the 137th Tactical Airlift Wing of the Oklahoma Air National Guard marked the first time an ANG airlift unit was equipped with brand new transport aircraft: it received four factory-fresh C-130H Hercules aircraft.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Several years later, Congress institutionalized the practice of purchasing limited amounts of new weapons and equipment for the reserve components via National Guard and Reserve Equipment (NG&RE) funding allocations.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Under the auspices of this separate appropriation for Guard and Reserve equipment established in 1982 under President Ronald Reagan, 69 brand new C-130s entered the ANG's inventory from 1984 to 1991.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] In July 1972, Air National Guard units began supporting Air Force tanker task forces overseas with second-line KC-97 Stratofreighter propeller-driven tankers and volunteer crews when needed.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Triggered by a 1974 decision by Secretary of Defense James R.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Schlesinger to save money, the Ohio Air National Guard's 145th Air Refueling Squadron acquired the ANG's first jet tanker in April 1975 when it began converting from KC-97Ls to KC-135A Stratotankers.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Altogether, the Air Force transferred 128 older KC-135s to the air reserve components to retire the slow prop-driven tankers, which modern fighters had to reduce speed to nearly stall speed in order to refuel from.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] During the 1980s, changes in the Air National Guard's force structure and readiness were primarily driven by President Reagan's military buildup and the need to prepare for a possible war between the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) and the Warsaw Pact in Central Europe.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] The ANG focused on modernization, more realistic combat training, increased readiness, and personnel growth, primarily in nonflying, mission support units.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] In 1979, Tactical Air Command assumed the atmospheric air defense mission of the United States with the inactivation of Aerospace Defense Command (ADCOM or ADC).
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] ADC fighter interceptor units were initially realigned into a component called Air Defense, Tactical Air Command (ADTAC), at the level of an Air Division.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] In 1985, First Air Force (1 AF) was reactivated by TAC and given the mission to provide, train and equip ADTAC combat ready forces.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Upon its reactivation, First Air Force was composed of units of both the active Air Force and the Air National Guard.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] In the years since its third activation, more of the responsibility for the defense of American air sovereignty was shifted to the Air National Guard.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] By the 1990s, 90 percent of the air defense mission was being handled by the Air National Guard.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] In October 1997, First Air Force became an Air National Guard numbered air force, charged with the air defense of the North American continent.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Instead of increasing the number of units, the National Guard Bureau authorized units to increase the number of aircraft assigned to them when the Air Force made those planes available.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] In 1982, the South Carolina Air National Guard's 169th Tactical Fighter Group began receiving new General Dynamics F-16A Fighting Falcons.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] In Air Force-wide competitions, ANG units and individuals frequently placed high or won.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] The 169th Tactical Fighter Group garnered top team honors in the Air Force's worldwide gunnery contest, Gunsmoke '89.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] The expiration of the Soviet Union, beginning with the fall of the Berlin Wall and Glasnost in 1989 and culminating in the USSR's breakup into its republics in 1991, constituted a major upheaval that continued to influence global politics into the 21st century.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] In December 1989 and January 1990, ANG volunteers participated in Operation Just Cause, the invasion of Panama, to secure the arrest of Panamanian dictator and accused drug lord, General Manuel Noriega.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Air National Guard aircrews already deployed TDY to Howard AFB, Panama also participated in Just Cause.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Volunteer C-130 crews completed 181 sorties moving 3,107 passengers and 551.3 tons of cargo.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] In addition, Air National Guard A-7 Corsair II attack jets from the South Dakota Air National Guard's 114th Tactical Fighter Group and the Ohio Air National Guard's 180th Tactical Fighter Group flew 34 combat missions in support of the invasion.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] However, the Air National Guard and the Total Force concept would be fully tested in the two major operations of the 1990s: Operation Desert Shield and the first Gulf War, Operation Desert Storm.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] In August 1990, ANG F-15 and F-16 fighter units initiated similar rotational service for Operation Coronet Nighthawk, the successor to Operation Volant Oak, out of Howard Air Force Base, Panama.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Those units monitored suspected airborne drug traffickers transiting Central America as well as the adjacent oceans.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] As the 1999 transfer of the Panama Canal to Panama approached, the Air National Guard began turning the operation over to civilian contractors.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] The last air national guardsmen completed their deployments to these South American sites in 1999.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Following the seizure of Kuwait by Iraqi forces in August 1990, the Air Force turned to both of its reserve components for help and was swamped with volunteers.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Bush mobilized reservists and national guardsmen on 22 August 1990, nearly 1,300 air national guardsmen actually entered active duty as volunteers.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Initially, most of them concentrated on aerial refueling and airlifting American forces to the Persian Gulf region.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] The first two ANG units to volunteer before the president's mobilization order were the 105th Military Airlift Group of the New York Air National Guard, and the 172nd Military Airlift Group of the Mississippi Air National Guard.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Respectively, they flew the C-5A Galaxy and the C-141B Starlifter.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Altogether, 12,456 air national guardsmen participated in Air Force operations during the Persian Gulf crisis/first Gulf War.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] When called upon, air national guardsmen were immediately prepared to perform their missions alongside their active Air Force counterparts.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] They did not need additional training or new equipment to do their jobs.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] They were integrated into most of the Air Force's operational missions, flying strategic airlift and aerial refueling sorties, and manning aerial ports.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Air national guardsmen also flew fighter, attack, aerial reconnaissance, special operations, and tactical theater airlift missions.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Compared to previous mobilizations, ANG units and individuals during Operations Desert Shield and Desert Storm were much better prepared to perform their missions upon entry into federal service.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Units were well equipped and well trained.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] As planned, they were able to respond much more rapidly and effectively than in previous call-ups.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] They were integrated into operations with their active duty and Air Force Reserve counterparts with a minimum of disruption and delay.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] In a new concept at the time, relatively few ANG outfits were mobilized as units.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Instead, the Air Force called up packages of equipment and personnel that were developed after the crisis began.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Mobilizing entire flying units and maintaining their integrity while in federal service, although desirable, would no longer be the only acceptable approach to supporting the Air Force in a crisis.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] Instead the Air National Guard would be flexible in its response in order to fit the situation.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p01] That could involve individual volunteers, tailored packages of volunteers, or mobilized air national guardsmen developed in response to specific contingencies.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] After the first Gulf War ended in 1991, air power continued to play a significant role in containing Saddam Hussein's regime in Iraq, as did a naval blockade and United Nations economic sanctions.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Together those forces also crippled the economic and military foundations of Hussein's power.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The Air National Guard participated widely in that long campaign, which featured U.S. and Coalition aircraft maintaining two no-fly zones over portions of Iraq: Operation Southern Watch (OSW) and Operation Northern Watch (ONW).
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] In addition, ANG units provided humanitarian aid to the Kurdish population in northern Iraq.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Later deploying units to Turkey participated in Operation Northern Watch that was focused strictly on enforcing the no-fly zone above the 36th parallel in Iraq as mandated by the UN and did not include humanitarian relief for the Kurds.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Following the first Gulf War, the Air National Guard's senior leadership in the National Guard Bureau began to adapt their organization for the post-Cold War era in a series of far-reaching discussions with top echelon Air Force personnel, state officials, unit leaders, and members of Congress.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Essentially, the Air Force agreed it would attempt to retain all ANG and Air Force Reserve flying units, while reducing its own as a cost-effective way to maintain a post-Cold War force structure.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] However, as limited amounts of newer equipment became available from a smaller Air Force, and budgets tightened, the ANG would reduce the numbers of aircraft assigned to each unit.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] If necessary, it would combine units at the same locations.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Some organizations would close down, but only as a last resort.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Aided by the newer aircraft from the shrinking Air Force inventory, the Air National Guard modernized and reshaped its fleet after the Cold War.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The size and composition of the ANG's aircraft inventory changed significantly after 1991.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] From 1991 to 2001 the ANG experienced an enormous growth in large aircraft including C-130H Hercules tactical airlifters, upgraded KC-135E and KC-135R Stratotankers, and Rockwell B-1B Lancer strategic bombers at the expense of smaller fighter planes.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] One of the most critical modernization challenges facing the ANG involved its extensive fleet of older model F-16As and F-16Bs.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] As its goal, the ANG sought to acquire F-16C Block 25/30/32 aircraft, enabling ANG fighter units to have around-the-clock, all-weather, precision strike capabilities against surface targets.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] In the general military drawdown following the end of the Cold War, many European-based F-15C Eagles previously assigned to USAFE were also transferred stateside.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The 101st Fighter Squadron of the Massachusetts Air National Guard received new F-15Cs that were previously with the 32nd Fighter Group, Soesterberg AB, Netherlands in 1994.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Other F-15A / F-15B units were upgraded to the F-15C and F-15D as they became available during the mid-1990s.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Most flying unit designations were simplified to "Airlift" or "Fighter" or "Air Refueling" or "Rescue", with flying squadrons being assigned to Operations Groups.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Also, on 1 October 1994, in accordance with the USAF "one base-one wing" policy, all Air National Guard flying units previously designated as a "group" had their status changed to a "wing" no later than 1 October 1995.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Additionally, ANG stations hosting flying units were re-designated as an "Air National Guard Base" if they were not collocated on an active duty installation.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Other overseas operations during the 1990s took air national guardsmen to Somalia, the former Yugoslavia, Haiti, and Rwanda to augment the Air Force in a series of contingencies and humanitarian relief operations.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Air National Guard and Air Force Reserve units would generally assume responsibility for an operation for 30 to 90 days, and then rotate their personnel on 15- to 30-day tours to a given location until the commitment ended.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] In July 1992, crews and C-130s from West Virginia's 167th Airlift Group inaugurated ANG involvement in Operation Provide Promise by flying food and relief supplies from Rhein-Main AB, Germany to Sarajevo, Bosnia's capital, which had a population of 380,000.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] That operation expanded significantly the following February to include airdrops of food and medicine to Muslim enclaves in eastern Bosnia blockaded by Bosnian Serbs.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Altogether, personnel and C-130s from 12 ANG units participated in Provide Promise.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] During the operation, Air Force, ANG, and Air Force Reserve transports flew 4,533 sorties and delivered 62,802 metric tons of cargo.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] They performed airlift, airdrop, and medical evacuation missions.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The Americans made a major contribution to the overall allied effort, which involved airmen from 21 nations.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The humanitarian airlift operation accounted for about 95 percent of the aid delivered during the 3+1⁄2-year siege of Sarajevo.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] On 2 April 1993, NATO troops from Great Britain, France, the Netherlands, Spain, Turkey, Germany, and Italy as well as the United States launched Operation Deny Flight, a no-fly zone for Serbian aircraft over Bosnia-Herzegovina.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] It enforced a March 1993 UN Security Council Resolution passed to help prevent the war from spreading.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The operation also provided close air support to UN Protection Force ground troops serving as peacekeepers, and airstrikes against Serb weapons threatening UN-designated safe areas in Bosnia.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The first ANG fighter unit involved was the Connecticut Air National Guard's A-10-equipped 103rd Fighter Group.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Aircraft and personnel from the Maryland Air National Guard's 175th Fighter Group and Michigan Air National Guard's 110th Fighter Group joined the contingent from Connecticut.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Along with unit personnel, the six Air National Guard and six Air Force Reserve A-10s returned to their home stations in mid-January 1994 after flying 520 sorties and accumulating over 1,400 hours of Deny Flight flying time.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Air National Guard tanker support of Deny Flight began in June 1994 with the dispatch of 10 KC-135s and 18 aircrews from six units to Istres Air Base, France, and Pisa Airport, Italy.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] By the time Deny Flight ended on 20 December 1995, elements of seven Air Guard fighter and 11 air refueling units had participated in it.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Operation Deliberate Force, was initiated in August 1995 after the Bosnian Serb army shelled a Sarajevo marketplace killing 43 civilians and wounding 75 more.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] A contingent from the 104th Fighter Wing participated in the action.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The intensity of the bombing stunned the Serbs.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Coupled with victories of an American-trained Croatian-Muslim army in western Bosnia, that operation forced the Serbs to sue for peace.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] NATO halted the bombing on 14 September 1995, and ended Deliberate Force six days later.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The Air National Guard returned to the Balkans in the mid-1990s as part of the NATO-led peacekeeping force in Bosnia, Operation Joint Guard, and its successor, Operation Joint Forge.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Volunteers from 13 Air National Guard airlift units provided 71 C-130s to Joint Forge.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] On average, ANG airlift deployment packages consisted of approximately 75 personnel and two C-130 aircraft.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] They were based at Ramstein AB, Germany, to provide the necessary airlift support for U.S. military forces in Bosnia-Herzegovina and other locations across Europe.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] In August 1998, the Air Force inaugurated a new concept.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] AEFs would rotate in order to ease the strain of increased post-Cold War operations overseas.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The AEF promised to spread the burden of deployments more widely among flying units, Active Duty, Air Force Reserve or Air National Guard.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Moreover, the timing of rotations became more predictable.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Greater predictability would enable Airmen, especially those in the Air Reserve Component, to better manage the competing demands of families, civilian careers, and military service.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Air National Guard aviation units would be expected to deploy overseas once every 15 months while support units would do so at 30-month intervals.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Driven by those requirements, Air National Guard planners in the National Guard Bureau began to "reengineer" ANG units to better participate in their expeditionary roles.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The benefits of this concept became apparent in the events of the early 2000s.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Defining events for the Air National Guard (ANG) as well as for the United States occurred with the al Qaeda attacks of 11 September 2001 on the World Trade Center in New York City and the Pentagon in Washington, D.C.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The only air defense fighter units stationed within the entire northeastern United States belonged to the Air National Guard.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] At 8:38 am, the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) in Boston, Massachusetts, reported a possible hijacking and called the Otis Air National Guard Base control tower on Cape Cod, home to the Massachusetts ANG's 102nd Fighter Wing, to request military assistance.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] At that time, Major Dan Nash and Lieutenant Colonel Tim Duffy had air defense alert duty for the 102nd.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] At 8:40 am Colonel Bob Marr, a Massachusetts air national guardsman serving as NORAD's Northeast Air Defense Sector commander, learned from the FAA that American Airlines Flight 11 might have been hijacked.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The two pilots immediately suited up and headed for their F-15s.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Marr ordered Nash and Duffy into the air; their F-15s were airborne within six minutes and as directed, headed for New York City, 153 miles away.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Unknown to the pilots, American Airlines Flight 11 had crashed into the North Tower of the World Trade Center in New York City just as Colonel Marr was delivering his order.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Meanwhile, at 8:43 am, the FAA reported another possible hijacking to the Northeast Air Defense Sector.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] That was Boston to Los Angeles United Airlines Flight 175.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] At 9:02 am, with the F-15s still 71 miles away, that plane crashed into the World Trade Center's South Tower.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] At 9:09 am the pilots of the North Dakota Air National Guards F-16s of the 119th Fighter Wing were standing by, ready to launch, at their forward alert operating location at Langley AFB, Virginia, located about 130 miles southeast of Washington, DC.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] They were at their battle stations because of a growing general concern about the situation that morning.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Seven minutes later, the FAA reported that United Airlines Flight 93, outbound from Newark, New Jersey, to San Francisco, California, might also have been hijacked.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The FAA notified the Northeast Air Defense Sector eight minutes later that American Flight 77, a flight from Dulles International Airport, Virginia, near Washington, DC, to Los Angeles, California, also appeared to be the victim of hijackers.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] At 9:24 am Colonel Marr ordered three F-16s (two alert aircraft and a spare) scrambled from Langley AFB to check out an unidentified intermittent aircraft track heading toward Washington DC.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] In six minutes, the Langley F-16s were airborne.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] In accordance with established NORAD procedures, the F-16s were initially directed to head northeast to avoid some of the most heavily traveled commercial airline routes rather than to fly directly to the Washington, DC, area.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Major Dean Eckmann and Major Brad Derrig, plus Captain Craig Borgstrom of the 119th Fighter Wing were directed to fly at maximum subsonic speed, 660 miles per hour.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] At about 40 miles away, they saw the billowing smoke of American Airlines Flight 77, which had crashed into the Pentagon at 9:43 am.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] As the North Dakota air guardsmen neared Washington, DC, Major Eckmann, the flight lead, set up a patrol over the nation's capital with the help of air traffic controllers at the Northeast Air Defense Sector.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] On 22 May 2002, a Joint Resolution was passed by the United States Congress recognizing the members of the 102nd Fighter Wing for their actions on 11 September 2001.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] As a result of the September 11 attacks in 2001, homeland defense became the top national defense priority.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The enhanced defense of North America and military support to civilian government agencies, known as Operation Noble Eagle, began early the next day.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] During the first 24 hours of the crisis, 34 Air National Guard fighter units flew 179 missions.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Eighteen tanker units generated 78 aircraft in the same time period.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Through 28 September, for example, the Alabama Air National Guard's 117th Air Refueling Wing kept aircraft aloft on a continuous basis.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Air National Guard units also contributed 111 C-130 aircraft for movement of personnel and equipment to needed locations, and more than 3,000 ANG security forces personnel supported the mission, augmenting civilian security police as necessary.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] A week after the attacks, Secretary of Defense Donald Rumsfeld announced the call up of over more than 5,000 members of the Air National Guard and Air Force Reserve to support the nation's increased security requirements.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Bush mobilized about 5,100 more members of the air reserve components, including approximately 3,000 air refueling and about 130 security specialists.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Guardsmen gained national visibility starting 27 September when President George W.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Bush asked the governors for their temporary help at commercial airports, which had reopened a few days after 9/11 with new security restrictions.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Although the Army Guard provided the vast majority of the enhanced airport security force, several hundred Air National Guard personnel also participated.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Combat Air Patrols (CAPs) began to be flown 24/7 over major cities in the United States.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] ANG squadrons at 26 bases were put at tremendous strain to support the operations.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The Air National Guard ran continuous round-the-clock combat air patrols over New York City and Washington, D.C., until spring 2002.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] In addition, when key events occurred such as the 2002 Winter Olympics in Utah, Space Shuttle launches in Florida, baseball's World Series and football's Super Bowl, similar air patrols helped provide security.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Because estimates of the nation's security situation became more optimistic, in spring 2002, the Air Force eliminated the continuous patrols and substituted random ones by the summer.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] On 20 September 2001, President Bush told a televised joint session of Congress and the American people that Osama bin Laden and his al Qaeda network were responsible for the recent terrorist attacks on the United States.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The refusal of the Taliban to comply resulted in the United States taking military action to achieve the president's demands, the action given the name Operation Enduring Freedom.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The ANG was involved even before the fighting in Afghanistan began.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] With the war imminent, the Air Force quickly established an airlift operations plan that included active duty, Guard, and Reserve components.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] It became one of the most extensive operations in Air Force history.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Furthermore, the Air Force met the logistical needs of that operation despite the severe shortage of strategic airlift and troublesome maintenance needs of the older planes.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Shortly after the terrorist attacks on 9/11 and weeks before the first U.S. bomb was dropped over Afghanistan, the Air Force established air bridges to help funnel material and personnel overseas to support multiple operations in conjunction with Enduring Freedom.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Air National Guard tanker units received orders by 20 September 2001, to be in their deployed locations before the start of their air bridge operations.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Some ANG tanker units also flew humanitarian support missions.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] By using European bases, the Air Force could transfer cargo from the larger aircraft to smaller planes, refuel aircraft on the ground, exchange flight crews, give crews rest opportunities, and repair broken aircraft.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The Air National Guard contributed two C-141 Starlifter units, the 155th Airlift Squadron / 164th Airlift Wing, Tennessee Air National Guard; and the 183rd Airlift Squadron / 172nd Airlift Wing, Mississippi Air National Guard, to the strategic airlift mission.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The Air National Guard's sole C-5 Galaxy unit, the 137th Airlift Squadron / 105th Airlift Wing, New York Air National Guard at Stewart Air National Guard Base in Newburgh, New York, also contributed to the operation.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Through the ANG's airlift participation in Europe, the Regular Air Force and Air Force Reserve (Associate) C-17 Globemaster IIIs could support Enduring Freedom directly.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] When the war began, only Air National Guard units assigned to Air Force Special Operations Command deployed directly to Afghanistan to support combat operations.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Typically, ANG special operations units in 13-man teams first went to active duty bases in the United States, and later to overseas locations.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The 169th Fighter Wing, South Carolina Air National Guard, was the first ANG fighter unit to deploy to Southwest Asia in direct support of the air war over Afghanistan.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] It sent over 200 personnel and six F-16CJs in January 2002 to Al Udeid Air Base in Doha, Qatar, to assist air combat operations over Afghanistan.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] In particular, they provided Joint Direct Attack Munitions (JDAMs) against Taliban and al Qaeda positions, the only Air Force fighter unit in the theater to do so.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] F-16s sometimes were also configured for Cluster Bomb Units (CBUw).
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] In addition, F-16 pilots sometimes fired their 20mm gun against ground targets.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Missions could last up to 10 hours with multiple air refuelings.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] After so many hours strapped in their seats, pilots generally received one to three days of crew rest.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The unit returned to South Carolina on 3 April 2002.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The Pennsylvania Air National Guard's 103rd Fighter Squadron of the 111th Fighter Wing, became the first A-10 ANG unit to deploy directly to Afghanistan.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] From December 2002 to January 2003, the 111th Fighter Wing deployed personnel and sent its aircraft to Bagram Air Base, Afghanistan to carry out ground support missions for both United States as well as Afghan Northern Alliance ground forces.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] In March 2003, the 104th Fighter Squadron of Maryland's 175th Wing deployed to Afghanistan.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] While there, it flew all the A-10 combat missions for Operation Enduring Freedom.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] For Operation Anaconda, its commander, Army Major General Franklin L.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Hagenbeck, directed coalition forces, U.S. soldiers and Afghan forces, to destroy remaining al Qaeda and Taliban forces in an area located roughly 65 nautical miles south of the Afghan capital, Kabul.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] One reconnaissance team in two helicopters landed on Takur Ghar, Ghar, a snowcapped, 10,200-foot mountain where temperatures at the top reached 40 °F (4 °C) during the day and dropped to a negative five at night.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] One helicopter carried a Navy SEAL team and an Air Force combat controller, Technical Sergeant John Chapman.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] As the SEAL team disem-barked, automatic weapons fire laced the helicopter's side while a rocket propelled grenade ripped into it.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The crew chief yelled, "We're taking fire!
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Go!" and the SEAL team rushed back inside.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] As the pilots added power to evade the heavy ground fire, the damaged helicopter bucked violently, causing Navy SEAL Petty Officer 1st Class Neil Roberts, who was standing on the ramp, to fall about 12 feet to the ground below.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The helicopter escaped the ambush and crash-landed about seven kilometers north of where Petty Officer Roberts fell.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The second helicopter rescued the other SEALs and Sergeant Chapman but after returning to their base, they decided to try and rescue Petty Officer Roberts.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Regardless of the danger they knew the al Qaeda would treat Roberts badly and time was running out for him.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Despite intense ground fire, the six men successfully returned to Takur Ghar.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Nevertheless, the battle continued and Sergeant Chapman was killed along with several enemy fighters.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Surrounded by gunfire, the men on the ground called upon a Quick Reaction Force (QRF), designed for such emergencies.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Those forces consisted of 23 men and two helicopters.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] "We were notified that we would be launching in 45 minutes," he recalled, "and were going into [an al Qaeda and Taliban] infested area." Also on the team were Army Rangers.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] During Operation Enduring Freedom, Rangers and special operations formed the focal point of the U.S. ground campaign.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Because of communications failures, the Quick Reaction Force landed in the same spot as the previous helicopters and, like them, was greeted with gunfire.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Miller's helicopter managed to land, and the QRF called in close air support.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] For the next five and a half hours, they battled with the enemy.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Three Rangers died and others were wounded.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] According to Sergeant Miller, "We continued to treat the patients, continued moving ammunition and grenades to where they were needed.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] I grabbed a radio … and set up satellite communication and then returned to the rear." Tech Sergeant Miller and Senior Airman Jason Cunningham, like Miller, a pararescueman, worked hard to keep the patients from succumbing to hypothermia.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] They put them in the helicopter and removed its insulation and wrapped it around the wounded Rangers.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] In addition, they used the majority of the fluids available in the medical kits and anything else, including the heaters packed in their food rations.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] With the help of the additional Rangers and more air strikes, they took the hill, killing many al Qaeda combatants.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] They also recovered the bodies of Petty Officer Roberts and Sergeant Chapman.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Approximately 10 minutes after the Rangers took control of the hill, they began to receive more frequent enemy mortar and automatic weapons fire.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Although combat air support prevailed, the enemy wounded an Army medic and fatally wounded Airman Cunningham.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] At that point the Quick Reaction Force had 11 wounded and seven dead.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] After 17 hours on the mountaintop, a nighttime rescue took place and the ordeal was over.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Operation Anaconda continued for another 19 days.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] By March 2002, ANG C-130 units had flown 55 percent of the missions for the Afghanistan war.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The 193rd Special Operations Wing of the Pennsylvania Air National Guard, using the EC-130E Commando Solo aircraft, performed an unusual mission in Afghanistan: psychological operations (PSYOPS).
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Since 1968, the 193rd had been handling airborne psychological operations missions.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The EC-130E acquired the mission name Commando Solo during the 1990s, when the aircraft was modified to handle color television operations.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] One of the first ANG flying units deployed to the area, the 193rd began transmitting by the end of October 2001.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] For almost six months the unit relayed broadcasts of Voice of America in the Dari and Pashtu languages and Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty in Uzbek, Tajik, and Persian.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Once the Iraq conflict began in March 2003, the military began to reduce its resources in Afghanistan.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Yet the reliance on using the Air National Guard and Air Force Reserve units, aircraft and personnel there continues to the present supporting the combat operations under United States Air Forces Central (USAFCENT).
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Air national guardsmen and aircraft deploy to Afghanistan routinely as part of the Air Expeditionary Units at bases there.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] On 18 March 2003, the United States and coalition forces launched the invasion of Iraq in order to remove Saddam Hussein's regime from power, the invasion being designated Operation Iraqi Freedom.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] As operations began, Army Rangers embarked on a mission to protect the Haditha Dam from being destroyed by Iraqi forces.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The Rangers expected the operation to last approximately 24 hours.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The dam is a critical source of water and electrical in western Iraq.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] If the Iraqis succeeded in blowing up the dam, the releasing waters would flood the down-river areas, causing a humanitarian and environmental disaster.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The Rangers expected the dam to be well defended.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] In preparation for the assault on the dam, fighters assigned to the 410th Air Expeditionary Wing (410 AEW) conducted preparatory air strikes against Iraqi forces in the dam's vicinity.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Air support for special forces in the battle came from various coalition aircraft including U.S.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] However, that battle became one of the defining operations for the AEW, and in particular, Air National Guard pilots.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The 410th was responsible for providing combat search and rescue capability for western and central Iraq.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] During the month-long air campaign over the western Iraqi desert, the A-10 and F-16 Air National Guard pilots assigned to the AEW were involved in countless missions supporting special forces teams in need of close air support.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The highly experienced Air National Guard pilots assigned to the AEW, especially the A-10 pilots, helped ensure the successful employment of close air support for friendly forces fighting to retain the Haditha Dam.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Army's 160th Special Operations Aviation Regiment and F-16s from the 410 AEW provided air cover as the Rangers took their convoy to Haditha.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] During the night of 1 April 2003, with support from the 410th, the Rangers seized the dam, a power station, and a transformer yard while facing light to moderate enemy resistance.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Several Iraqis were killed and wounded; others, including 25 civilian workers, were taken prisoner.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] As daylight broke over the dam, the Rangers began taking increasing enemy fire from the south as well as coordinated attacks at both ends of the dam.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Although the Rangers repelled the initial assault, Iraqi counterattacks continued with heavy mortar and artillery shells that rained down on the Rangers.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Fortunately, the Rangers had ample air support from the 410th which attacked several mortar positions.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Even without the protection of darkness, the Air National Guard A-10s attacked numerous enemy positions.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] At nightfall the Iraqis resumed their attacks against the Rangers, but once again close air supported the U.S. forces.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] A single bomb obliterated the attackers and shattered every window in the dam complex.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Nevertheless, the siege continued for ten more days.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The Rangers on the dam were greatly outnumbered.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The 410th fighters also supplied air cover during medical evacuation missions for killed and wounded Rangers.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] During the twelfth day of the siege, the outnumbered Rangers continued to face repeated attacks by the enemy force.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The Air National Guard A-10 and F-16 pilots realized early in the battle that the close air support they provided was the vital element that kept the Iraqi forces at bay, a matter of life and death for the Rangers.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] In the end the coalition forces prevailed.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Military experts believed that without the air support, especially the A-10s, the Rangers would not have won the battle.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Not only did the coalition forces secure the Haditha Dam complex, but they seriously reduced the fighting effectiveness of the Iraqi Armored Task Force in the Haditha area.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Operation Iraqi Freedom's intelligence collection efforts were enhanced by the initial combat employment of the Air Force's first and only "blended" wing: the newly formed 116th Air Control Wing, composed of both ANG and active duty Air Force personnel based in Robins AFB, Georgia.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The wing deployed nine of its 11 assigned E-8 Joint STARS aircraft to the Iraqi Freedom theater as well as over 600 unit personnel including one-tenth of the aircrews.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Air National Guardsmen composed about one-fourth of the Wing's deployed personnel.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Although the wing has since reverted to an all-ANG organization, it continues to be integral to operation of the E-8 Joint STARS weapon system.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The 193rd Special Operations Wing of the Pennsylvania Air National Guard deployed its EC-130 Commando Solo aircraft for a variety of PSYOPS support to coalition agencies in Iraq.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Flying from March to June 2003, its missions apparently fulfilled their goals.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] According to an Iraqi prisoner of war and former mid-level intelligence officer, the population in southern Iraq considered the coalition radio broadcasts more truthful than state-owned media.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The leaflets also had a significant impact on the morale of Iraqi military and prompted considerations to surrender.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The Iraqis concluded that U.S. planes could as easily target them with bombs as leaflets if their intent was lethal.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] As in Afghanistan, the Air National Guard contributed significant airlift capability to Operation Iraqi Freedom.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Thirteen of ANG's 25 airlift units participated, including 72 of 124 Air Force C-130s.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Among their missions, Air National Guard C-130 crews airlifted elements of the 82nd Airborne Division and the 3rd Marine Expeditionary Force.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Those crews also flew one of the first day/night airlift missions into an Iraqi air base and delivered the first humanitarian supplies into Baghdad International Airport.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] During Operation Iraqi Freedom's first six months, Air National Guard C-130 crews airlifted 22,000 tons of cargo, 47,000 passengers, and flew 8,600 sorties in 21,000 hours.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] As essential to the war effort as were C-130s, A-10s, and piloted reconnaissance and surveillance aircraft, they could not have completed their missions efficiently without aerial refueling.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] During the war in Iraq, the Air Force deployed 200 tanker aircraft based at 15 locations.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Air National Guard KC-135 tankers provided one-third of the Air Force refueling aircraft deployed for Operation Iraqi Freedom, and an additional 35 ANG tanker aircraft conducted air bridge operations.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The Air National Guard also deployed air traffic control personnel, maintainers, and airspace managers.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Over 27 percent of the total Air Force civil engineering force in Iraq came from the ANG; other Air Guard engineers supported Iraqi Freedom while operating in several other countries.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The Iraqi conflict continued through 2011 and the Air National Guard continued its involvement.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] By 2004 nearly 40 percent of the total Air Force aircraft deployed for overseas operations were assigned to the Air National Guard.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The ANG supported Air Expeditionary Force deployments to Iraq throughout the 2000s, until the withdrawal of U.S. troops from Iraq in 2011.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Traditionally, governors called out National Guard units when faced with natural but localized disasters such as blizzards, earthquakes, floods, and forest fires.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The president could also federalize them in major disasters that threatened to overwhelm the resources of individual states or communities.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Housed in C-130s, MAFFS could disperse up to 27,000 pounds ... almost 3,000 gallons ... of commercial fire retardants or an equivalent amount of water.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Newer aircraft like the C-130J carry the MAFFS II, which carry even more fire retardant, can disperse it more rapidly over a wider area, and is easier to recharge after a mission than its predecessor.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Blizzards also created the need for National Guard support.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Often both Army National Guard and Air National Guard units assisted with health and welfare matters, conducted debris removal and power generation, and provided supply and transportation support in connection with snowstorms.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] For example, a Christmas-time 2006 blizzard at the airport hub of Denver International Airport closed that facility down for two days.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Army and air national guardsmen took food and water to thousands of travelers trapped there.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] In the same storm, western Kansas received between 15 and 36 inches of snow with drifts as high as 13 feet.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The Air National Guard not only assisted people, but also dropped bales of hay to feed stranded cattle.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] On 29 August 2005, the largest natural disaster the Air National Guard faced in its then 58-year history began when Hurricane Katrina hit the United States Gulf Coast.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The most severe damage came from a 30-plus-foot storm surge along the Mississippi coast and the north shore of Lake Pontchartrain in Louisiana and breaks in the levies along a canal in New Orleans.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Several weeks later Hurricane Rita devastated portions of western Louisiana and eastern Texas, and then the less severe Hurricane Wilma damaged Florida.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] By the time Katrina made landfall, the Air National Guard had mobilized 840 personnel in Florida, Mississippi, Louisiana, and Texas.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Although the Air National Guard had a domestic mission to support local authorities in rescue and relief operations following a natural disaster, its utilization for such missions had been limited primarily to a select group of career fields such as civil engineers, medical personnel, and services.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The ANG flew 73 percent of the airlift for the relief operations including its brand new C-130J and C-17 Globemaster III aircraft.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] In addition, ANG Combat Search and Rescue pararescuemen and Combat Controllers saved over 1,300 victims.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] ANG personnel arrived on the Gulf Coast on 29 August, a few hours after the storm's arrival.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Personnel from the Florida Air National Guard's 202nd RED HORSE Squadron of the 125th Fighter Wing were some of the first to enter the area.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Seventy-three engineers from this unit worked in hard-hit Hancock County, Mississippi.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Initially establishing a basecamp for other emergency personnel, the unit began repairs in Hancock County communities working nearly around-the-clock on multiple construction projects to restore power, clean and repair schools, and refurbish electrical supplies.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] As a Florida unit, the 202nd had worked many other hurricanes.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] However, Katrina's devastation surpassed anything in their previous experience.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] To support rescue and relief operations in New Orleans, the Air National Guard used Naval Air Station Joint Reserve Base New Orleans, in Belle Chasse, Louisiana, on the Mississippi River's West Bank.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Within five hours of its orders, the 136th Airlift Wing of the Texas Air National Guard deployed 41 Air National Guardsmen to Belle Chasse.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Less than 24 hours later, a C-130H landed at the air station with members of the Louisiana Air National Guard's 159th Fighter Wing.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Soon more aircraft arrived, delivering troops and supplies for New Orleans; offloaded pallets were stacked 10 deep on the aircraft parking ramp.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Instead of heading into the flooded city, the 136th team remained at Belle Chasse and, within 36 hours of arriving, it established a fully functioning Air Terminal Operations Center and was keeping pace with the demanding mission schedule.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] That Aerial Port team, augmented by U.S.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Navy cargo handlers and members of the 133rd Aerial Port Squadron, 133rd Airlift Wing of the Minnesota Air National Guard, handled over 124 missions with 1.5 million pounds of cargo and 974 passengers in one day.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] As one of its most crucial tasks, the Texas squadron downloaded the German pump system used to drain the city of New Orleans because its own pumps were inundated.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] It also uploaded two KC-135s with 140 kennels filled with rescued dogs bound for adoption in Arizona.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The Air National Guard also participates in noncombat support missions that sometimes take it beyond the U.S. boundaries.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] For example, in Operation Winter Freeze, from November 2004 to January 2005, nearly 250 Army and air national guardsmen provided assistance to U.S.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Customs and Border Protection (CBP) along 295 miles of the United States-Canada border.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] That operation included military personnel from U.S.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Northern Command's Joint Task Force North who helped the Border Patrol to, "... keep potential terrorists out of the country and to break up smuggling rings that try to get them in." [In order] to detect, deter, and monitor suspicious actions ...
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The New York Air National Guard's 109th Airlift Wing operates ski-equipped LC-130 Hercules transports that fly into arctic regions.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] In 2006, two LC-130s closed the 2006 Operation Deep Freeze located at McMurdo Station near the South Pole.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The mission ended because the temperature dropped to almost minus −50 °F (−46 °C) in three days.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] Since 1988, the squadron had provided the air supply bridge to McMurdo, landing with wheels on an ice runway near the station.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] However, as it got colder, the ski-equipped LC-130s landed on a snow-covered skiway on the Ross Ice Shelf a few miles from the station.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] In the spring and summer, the 109th heads toward the North Pole where it supports the National Science Foundation and several other nations in Greenland and above the Arctic Circle.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] In April 2023, Jack Teixeira, a 21-year-old member of the intelligence wing of the Massachusetts Air National Guard, was arrested for unauthorized removal and transmission of classified US intelligence related to the Russian invasion of Ukraine.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The leaked documents, which first appeared in an online group linked to Teixeira, strained relations with American allies and exposed weaknesses in the Ukrainian military.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] The arrest was conducted by the FBI at Teixeira's residence in North Dighton, Massachusetts.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p02] On 11 December 2023, the United States Air Force disciplined 15 other individuals connected to the investigation of airman Jack Teixera.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] This is a list of the senior leaders or Generals of the Air National Guard.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] The title has changed over time: The Assistant Chief, National Guard Bureau for Air; Chief, Air Force Division, National Guard Bureau; Director Air National Guard.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] Established under Title 10 and Title 32 of the U.S.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] Code, the Air National Guard is part of the state National Guard and is divided up into units stationed in each of the 50 states, the District of Columbia (D.C.), the Commonwealth of Puerto Rico, Guam, and the United States Virgin Islands.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] The current distribution of ANG units and their associated authorized manpower slots is based on the respective state, district, commonwealth, or territorial population.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] However, this distribution of units, personnel, aircraft and resources is predicated on what those populations were in calendar year 1958 and has not been updated since.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] This has resulted in states with high population growth in the ensuing decades such as Florida having fewer ANG personnel relative to state population and fewer wings with unit-assigned aircraft than states such as Alabama, Pennsylvania, or West Virginia.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] ANG units typically operate under Title 32 USC.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] When operating under Title 10 USC all ANG units are operationally gained by an active-duty major command of the Air Force or the U.S.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] ANG units of the Combat Air Forces (CAF) based in the Continental United States (CONUS), plus a single air control squadron of the Puerto Rico ANG, are gained by the Air Combat Command (ACC).
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] CONUS-based ANG units in the Mobility Air Forces (MAF), plus the Puerto Rico ANG's airlift wing and the Virgin Islands ANG's civil engineering squadron are gained by the Air Mobility Command (AMC) The exception to this rule is the District of Columbia Air National Guard (DC ANG).
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] As a federal district, the units of the DC ANG are under the direct jurisdiction of the President of the United States through the office of the Commanding General, District of Columbia National Guard.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] In the "state" role, the Air National Guard may be "called up" for active duty by the governors to help respond to domestic emergencies and disasters, such as those caused by hurricanes, floods, fires, and earthquakes.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] Air National Guard, the Adjutant General of the District of Columbia reports to the Mayor of the District of Columbia, who may only activate DC Air Guard and Army Guard assets for limited activation after consultation and approval of the President of the United States.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] With the consent of the state governor, members or units of the Air National Guard may be appointed, temporarily or indefinitely, to be federally recognized members of the armed forces, in the active or inactive (e.g., reserve) service of the United States.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] If federally recognized, the member or unit becomes part of the **Air National Guard of the United States**, which is one of two reserve components of the U.S.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] Because both state and federal ANGs go relatively hand-in-hand, they are both usually referred to collectively.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] Air National Guardsmen who become members of the Active Guard and Reserve (AGR) receive full active duty pay and benefits just like active duty members of any branch of the armed forces.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] ANG units or members may be called up for federal active duty in times of Congressionally sanctioned war or national emergency.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] Many ANG pilots work for commercial airlines, but in the ANG they may train to fly any of the aircraft in the USAF inventory, with the current exception of the Rockwell B-1B Lancer and B-52 Stratofortress bombers, the C-5 Galaxy, E-3 Sentry AWACS aircraft, and the AC-130 Gunship.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] The Georgia Air National Guard and the Kansas Air National Guard previously flew the Rockwell B-1B Lancer prior to converting to the E-8 Joint STARS and KC-135R Stratotanker, respectively.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] In addition, the 131st Fighter Wing of the Missouri Air National Guard transitioned from flying the F-15C/D Eagle at St.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] Louis International Airport/Lambert Field Air National Guard Station to the B-2 Spirit at Whiteman Air Force Base as an "Associate" unit of the Regular Air Force's 509th Bomb Wing and was re-designated as the 131st Bomb Wing.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] Schwartz, the then-Chief of Staff of the Air Force, defended cutting nearly twice as many service members from the Air National Guard and the AFRC as from the active duty Regular Air Force in order to maintain the service's surge and rotational capabilities in the Active Component.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] These proposals were eventually overruled and cancelled by the U.S.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] Air National Guard operations are arranged according to U.S. state structure, so that each of the fifty states and Washington, D.C. host at least one wing.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] Guam, Puerto Rico and The US Virgin Islands each support a wing or support squadron.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] Some larger states such as California, Ohio, New York, and Texas host as many as five wings as well as smaller geographically separated units (GSUs).
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] Air National Guard wings are either assigned aircraft or, in some cases, operate as "non-flying" wings.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] Examples of non-flying wings include regional support wings and intelligence wings.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] For the most part, the ANG "own" their own equipment, but in some cases, aircraft and mission support operations are shared with active-duty Air Force or the Air Force Reserve.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] ANG stations may be located on or next to active-duty Air Force bases, Air Reserve bases, civilian airports, Naval Air stations, Army installations, or stand-alone Air National Guard stations.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] The majority of ANG wings fall under either ACC or AMC MAJCOMS.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] Some exceptions include the Alaska, Hawaii, and Guam wings, whose CAF and MAF units are operationally gained by Pacific Air Forces, and wings associated with U.S.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] Space Force, Air Education and Training Command, Air Force Global Strike Command, and Air Force Special Operations Command, and U.S.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] Air Forces in Europe – Air Forces Africa.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] Air National Guard had about 107,100 men and women in service.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] Like the Air Force Reserve Command (AFRC), most ANG members serve part-time at least one weekend a month and an additional two weeks a year (e.g., 38 days).
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] The demands of maintaining aircraft mean that some AFRC and ANG members work full-time, either as full-time Air Reserve Technicians (ART) or Active Guard and Reserve (AGR) personnel.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] Even traditional part-time air guardsmen, especially pilots, navigators/combat systems officers, air battle managers and enlisted aircrew, often serve 100 or more man-days annually.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] The Air National Guard and the Air Force Reserve Command (AFRC) comprise the "**Air Reserve Component**" of the U.S.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] Air Force under the "Total Force" construct.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] As state militia units, the units in the Air National Guard are not in the normal U.S.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] They are under the jurisdiction of the United States National Guard Bureau unless they are federalized by order of the President of the United States.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] The Air National Guard Readiness Center, a field operating center of the U.S.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] Air Force at Joint Base Andrews, Maryland, performs operational and technical functions to ensure combat readiness of ANG units and is a channel of communication between the Air Force and the National Guard Bureau regarding readiness and operations.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] Air National Guard units are trained and equipped by the U.S.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] The state (or equivalent) ANG units, depending on their mission, are operationally gained by a major command of the USAF if federalized.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] In addition, personnel and equipment are routinely federalized and deployed by the USAF as part of Air Expeditionary Forces.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] ANG enlisted members complete Basic Military Training at Joint Base San Antonio.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] Air National Guard personnel are expected to adhere to the same moral and physical standards as their "full-time" active duty Air Force and "part-time" Air Force Reserve federal counterparts.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] All Air National Guardsmen are eligible to receive all U.S. military awards.
[src:air-national-guard/air-national-guard-p03] The ANG also bestows a number of state awards for local services rendered in a service member's home state or equivalent.
